    <h2>
      CHAPTER VII.&mdash;THE THREE BROTHERS.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span>fter the early
      supper of stale bread, saltless butter, dark dried apple sauce, and chippy
      cake had been disposed of, Lemuel returned to his rocking chair by the
      stove, Aunt Sabrina and Isabel took seats, each at a window, and read by
      the fading light, and Albert put on his hat, lighted a cigar, and went
      out. His brother John stood smoking a pipe in the yard, leaning against
      the high well-curb, his hands deep in his pantaloons pocket, and his feet
      planted far to the front and wide apart. Seth was coming from the barns
      toward the well, with a bucket in his hand. Albert walked across to the
      curb, and the three brothers were alone together for the first time in
      years.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It does one good to be out of doors such an evening as this,&rdquo; said
      Albert. &ldquo;It seems to me it would be better if father would get out in the
      open air more, instead of sitting cooped up over that stove all the
      while.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When a man&rsquo;s been out in the open air, rain or shine, snow or blow, for
      fifty years, he ought to have earned the right to stay inside, if he wants
      to. | That&rsquo;s about the only reward there is at the end of a farmer&rsquo;s
      life,&rdquo; answered Seth, turning the calfbucket upside down beside John, and
      sitting on it. Seth had his old clothes on once more, and perhaps there
      was some consciousness of the contrast between his apparel and that of his
      black-clad brethren in the truculent tone of his reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      John had nodded at Albert on his approach, and thrust his feet a trifle
      further forward. He still stood silent, looking meditatively at the row of
      poplars on the other side of the road through rings of pipe smoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you don&rsquo;t think much of farm work, eh?&rdquo; said Albert.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who does?&rdquo; replied Seth, sententiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      A considerable period of silence ensued. Albert had never had a very high
      idea of his younger brothers&rsquo; conversational qualities, and had rarely
      known how to talk easily with them, but to-night it seemed a greater task
      than ever. He offered them cigars, in a propitiatory way. Seth accepted
      and lit one; John said &ldquo;Thanks, I prefer a pipe,&rdquo; and silence reigned
      again.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was twilight now, and in the gathering dusk there was no sign of motion
      about, nor any sound save the tinkle of a sheep-bell in the pasture
      opposite.
    </p>
    <p>
      John&rsquo;s pipe burned out, and Albert pressed a cigar upon him again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I <i>want</i> you to try them,&rdquo; he said, almost pleadingly, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sure
      you&rsquo;ll like them. They are a special brand the steward at the Union League
      gets for me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This time John consented, and he seemed to feel that the act involved a
      responsibility to talk, for he said, with an effort at amiability as he
      struck a match:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your wife seems to be looking very well.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, Isabel&rsquo;s health is perfect, and it always benefits her to get out in
      the country. That&rsquo;s a kind of Irishism isn&rsquo;t it? I mean it makes her good
      health more obvious.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good health is a great thing,&rdquo; John answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      The conversation was running emptings again, almost at the start. Albert
      made a heroic effort to strengthen it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, this is a regular quakers&rsquo; meeting,&rdquo; he said, briskly. &ldquo;We see each
      other so seldom, we are almost strangers when we do meet. I want to be
      frank with you, come now, and you should be frank with me. You have
      something on your minds, I can see. Isn&rsquo;t it something I ought to know?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Seth spoke again: &ldquo;Perhaps on the evening of one&rsquo;s mother&rsquo;s funeral it
      isn&rsquo;t to be expected that even brothers should feel chatty.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The village journalist felt the injustice of this comment from the
      youngster.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, Seth,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t snap Albert up in that fashion. I dare say he
      feels the thing, in his own way, as much as the rest of us. You are right,
      Albert; there <i>is</i> something, and I&rsquo;ll tell you plainly what it is.
      Do you see those poplars over there? In the morning their shadows Come
      almost to our front door. Father planted them with his own hands. When I
      was a boy, I used to play over there, and climb up on to the bolls, and
      pretend I was to build houses there, like in Swiss Family Robinson. Well,
      that land passed out of our hands so long ago&mdash;it&rsquo;s been an old story
      for years. Do you see the roof of the red school-house over back of the
      hill?&rdquo; turning toward the South. &ldquo;Or no, the light is too poor now, but
      you know where it is. When I used to cut &rsquo;cross lots to school
      there, I went the whole way over father&rsquo;s land. Now, if I wanted to go
      there, how many people would I trespass on, Seth?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ferguson owns the clover meadow, and Pratt has the timothy meadow, and
      what we used to call the berry patch belongs to Sile Thomas; he&rsquo;s begun to
      build a house on it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Precisely. Why even the fence close to where mother&rsquo;s grave is, divides
      ours from another man&rsquo;s land now.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sabrina spoke to me about all this this afternoon,&rdquo; said Albert
      hesitatingly, &ldquo;and I tried, as I often have before, to make her understand
      that that must be the natural course of affairs, so long as the East tries
      to compete with the West in farming.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well that may be all right, but Elhanan Pratt seems to manage to compete
      with the West, as you call it, and so do the Fergusons and all the rest of
      them. We are the only ones who appear to get left, every time. Of course,
      it&rsquo;s somebody&rsquo;s fault. Father&rsquo;s been a poor manager, no use of denying
      that. But that doesn&rsquo;t make it any the easier to bear. Father hardly knows
      which way to turn for ours from another man&rsquo;s now. Money; he might have
      scraped through the year if hops had had a good season, but at nine cents
      a pound it was hardly worth while to take them to the depot. You can&rsquo;t
      clear expenses at less than eleven cents. And then if he does have a
      fairly decent year, his hop-pickers are always the most drunken, idle gang
      of them all, who eat their heads off, and steal more fruit and chickens
      than they pick boxes, and if anybody&rsquo;s hops are spoiled in the kiln, you
      can bet on their being Fairchild&rsquo;s, every time. And three years ago, it
      was the hop merchant who failed, just at the opportune moment, and let
      Father in for a whole years&rsquo; profit and labor. Of course, it&rsquo;s all bad
      luck, mismanagement, whatever you like to call it, and it can&rsquo;t be helped,
      I suppose. But it makes a man sour, and it broke poor mother&rsquo;s heart. And
      then here&rsquo;s Seth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, never mind me, I can stand it, I guess, if the rest can. I&rsquo;m not
      complaining&rdquo; came from the figure on the bucket&mdash;only dimly to be
      seen now, in the shadow of the curb, and the increasing darkness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here&rsquo;s Seth,&rdquo; continued John, without noting the disclaimer. &ldquo;You and I
      had <i>some</i> advantages&mdash;of course, mine were not to be compared
      with yours, but still I was given a chance, such as it was and I don&rsquo;t
      know that I would trade what I learned at work during college years for a
      college education&mdash;but this poor boy, who&rsquo;s thought about him, who&rsquo;s
      given him a chance to show what&rsquo;s in him? He&rsquo;s been allowed to come up as
      he could, almost like any farm laborer. His mother tried to do her little,
      but what spirit did she have for it, and what time did the drudgery here
      give him? Thank God! He&rsquo;s had the stuff in him to work at education
      himself, and he&rsquo;s got the making of the best man of us three. But it&rsquo;s no
      thanks to you. And <i>that&rsquo;s</i> why we feel hard, Albert. Nobody supposes
      you could make a good farmer and manager out of father; nobody blames you
      for a bad hop season, or the dishonesty of Biggs. But I do say that of us
      three brothers there&rsquo;s one who frets and worries over the thing, and
      though he&rsquo;s a poor man, does all he can afford to do, and more too, to
      help make it better; and there&rsquo;s another, young, ambitious, capable, whose
      nose is held down to the grindstone, and the best years of whose life are
      being miserably spent in a hopeless wrestling with debt and disaster; and
      there&rsquo;s a third brother, the oldest brother, rich, easy, enjoying all the
      luxuries of life, who don&rsquo;t give a damn about it all! <i>That&rsquo;s</i> what I
      say, and if you don&rsquo;t like it, you needn&rsquo;t!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The silence which ensued was of the kind that can be felt. The two cigars
      at the corners of the old curb glowed intermittently in the darkness.
      John&rsquo;s had gone out during his speech, and as he re-lighted it, the glare
      of the match showed an excited, indignant face. There was no room for
      doubt, after the momentary exhibit which the red light made, that John was
      very much in earnest.
    </p>
    <p>
      Albert was thinking laboriously on his answer. Meantime, he said, to fill
      the interval &ldquo;Do you like the cigar?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes; a fifteen center, isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Albert had it in his mind to say truthfully that he paid $180 per
      thousand, but the fear of invidious comparisons rose before him in time,
      and he said &ldquo;About that, I think.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He waited a moment, still meditating, and threw out another stop-gap:
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s curious how the rhetorical habit grows on a man who writes leading
      articles. I noticed that you used three adjectives every time, the regular
      cumulative thing, you know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Maybe so; it would be more to the purpose to hear what you think about
      the spirit of my oration; the form doesn&rsquo;t matter so much.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I will tell you, John,&rdquo; said Albert, slowly, still feeling his way,
      &ldquo;to speak frankly, no doubt there&rsquo;s a good deal in what you say. I feel
      that there is. But you ought to consider that it isn&rsquo;t easy for a man
      living in a great city, immersed in business cares, and engrossed in the
      labors of his profession, to realise all these things, and see them as
      you, who are here on the ground, see them. It&rsquo;s hardly fair to attack me
      as heartless, when you present these facts to me for the first time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;For the first time! You ought to have seen them for yourself without
      presenting. And then you said Sabrina had often discussed the subject with
      you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, but her point of view is always family dignity, the keeping up of the
      Fairchilds&rsquo; homestead in baronial state, and that sort of thing. You
      should have heard her this afternoon, telling me how her fathers name used
      to be coupled with Dearborn County, just as Silas Wright&rsquo;s was with
      Dutchess&mdash;either Dutchess or Delaware, I forget which she said&mdash;but
      it was very funny.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sabrina and I haven&rsquo;t spoken for I don&rsquo;t know how long, and we&rsquo;re not
      likely to again in a hurry, but for all that I&rsquo;m bound to say I wish some
      others of the family had as much pride as she&rsquo;s got,&rdquo; said John. &ldquo;Whatever
      else she may be, she&rsquo;s as loyal and as faithful to the family idea, as
      jealous of the family&rsquo;s name, as any old Spanish grandee. And I confess
      the Silas Wright thing doesn&rsquo;t seem funny to me at all&mdash;any fellow
      with the right kind of a heart in him would feel that it was deucedly
      pathetic&mdash;the poor old maid clinging through the shipwreck to that
      one spar of support&mdash;the recollection of a time when her father was
      bigger than his county. Such things oughtn&rsquo;t to be laughed at.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Albert lost his patience. &ldquo;Confound it, man, do you want to force me into
      a quarrel&mdash;this night of all others! By George, was there ever such a
      brace of brothers! I come out here to get you by yourselves, to talk over
      with you some plans that have occurred to me for setting things right here&mdash;and
      I haven&rsquo;t had a civil answer yet from either of you. First it&rsquo;s the
      youngster who scowls and snarls at me, and then you read me lofty lectures
      on my behavior, and then both together in concerted condemnation. No
      wonder I come rarely to the farm! It&rsquo;s enough to sicken any man of family
      ties, to be bullyragged in this way. I&rsquo;ve a good mind to tell you you can
      all go to the devil, and be hanged to you!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The figure on the bucket rose to its feet with a spring, so energetically
      that there seemed a menace in the action. The village editor restrained
      this movement with a quiet hand, and a whispered &ldquo;Keep cool, Seth.&rdquo; Then
      he said with exaggerated calmness of voice:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Personally, perhaps I shouldn&rsquo;t mind much if you did. But there are
      others to look after, and so, before you do, it might be worth while to
      learn what the fine alternative was to have been. It would be a great pity
      to not even to hear these noble plans with which you were primed, you say,
      when you came out.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you must admit, John, that you and Seth tonight have been enough to
      try the patience of a saint.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes, we admit that. Go on!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you&rsquo;ve made it a little difficult for me to develop my plans&mdash;they
      were scarcely formed in my mind. In a general way, I wanted to consult you
      about freeing the farm, perhaps buying back some of the original land that
      has gone, putting the house in shape again, improving the stock, placing
      Father and Sabrina beyond the chance of ever being embarrassed again&mdash;and&mdash;and&mdash;doing
      something for Seth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nobody wants you&mdash;&rdquo; began the impatient Seth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Youngster, <i>you</i> shut up!&rdquo; said John, again using the quieting hand.
      &ldquo;Do you really mean all this, Albert?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should scarcely have spoken in detail as I have, otherwise,&rdquo; answered
      the lawyer loftily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, this&mdash;&rdquo; said John, &ldquo;this takes a fellow&rsquo;s breath away.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you hadn&rsquo;t been in such haste to impute bad motives and convict me
      without judge or jury, perhaps the effect of my plans might not have been
      so overpowering.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, we did you an injustice, Albert, clearly we did. We were full of the
      idea that all these troubles rolled off you like water off a duck&rsquo;s back.
      It seems that was our mistake. But&mdash;what&rsquo;s your scheme?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Definitely, I have none, except to do all I can, in the way we may decide
      will be best all around. I have been thinking some of coming to live here
      myself, say from May to November of each year, and taking the farm into my
      own hands.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;H&rsquo;m&mdash;m! That might have its advantages, perhaps&mdash;<i>but</i>&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I know what you mean. If I do, everybody&rsquo;s rights shall be respected.
      We&rsquo;ll fix that beyond question, to your satisfaction, before a thing is
      done.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t care about myself, particularly; you know that: but then there&rsquo;s
      Seth, you know&mdash;we&rsquo;ve always figured on the farm as his. It&rsquo;s true he
      don&rsquo;t want to be a farmer, that he hates the whole thing, but still that
      represents all his capital, so to speak, and&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My dear John, that shall all be arranged. I am a childless man&mdash;probably
      always shall be. As long as Father lives the farm shall remain in his
      name. Either his will can be in my favor, or I can manage the farm as a
      trustee for all three of us, after he&rsquo;s gone. In either case, you shall
      both be protected in turn by my will&mdash;absolutely protected. Meantime,
      what do you want me to do for Seth? What does he want to do?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nothing needs to be done for me,&rdquo; began Seth, &ldquo;I can&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Now, youngster, <i>will</i> you be quiet!&rdquo; said John, in mock despair.
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll tell you what you can do for Seth, and do easily. Get him a place on
      some decent newspaper, in New York or one of the larger cities of the
      State, and let him have money enough to eke out a small salary at first,
      so that he can begin at editorial work instead of tramping up through the
      reporter&rsquo;s treadmill, as I had to. That&rsquo;s all Seth&rsquo;ll ask, and it will be
      the making of him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Begin at editorial work&mdash;Seth? Nonsense!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No nonsense about it. For two years back Seth has been doing some of the
      best work on my paper&mdash;work that&rsquo;s been copied all over the State.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bless my soul, what a literary family we are!&rdquo; said the lawyer. &ldquo;Does
      Aunt Sabrina write, too? Perhaps those love poems you have on the last
      page are hers.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      John continued without noticing the interjection. &ldquo;Do you remember that
      long article on Civil Service Reform we had in the <i>Banner</i> last
      January?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think I do, John. To be frank, although we enjoy having you send
      us the <i>Banner</i> immensely, occasionally it happens that the stress of
      professional duties compels me to miss reading a number.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well that article was reprinted in all the big papers, from Boston to
      Chicago. I never knew any other thing from a little village paper to
      travel so far, or attract so much attention. I had lots of letters about
      it, too. That article was Seth&rsquo;s&mdash;all his own. I didn&rsquo;t change a word
      in it. And he&rsquo;s hardly seen any thing of the world yet, either.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The lawyer was heard chuckling, when John&rsquo;s voice died away in the
      darkness. The cigars had long since burned out, and the men could with
      difficulty see one another. The two younger brothers waited, the one
      surprised, the other increasingly indignant, to learn the cause of
      Albert&rsquo;s hilarity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you realise, John,&rdquo; he said at last, with merriment still in his
      voice, &ldquo;what a delightful commentary on Civil Service Reform your words
      make. The best article on that doctrine is written by a youngster who has
      never left the farm, who doesn&rsquo;t know the difference between a Custom
      House and a letter-box on a lamp-post! Ho, ho, I must tell that to
      Chauncey when I see him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      An hour later, John and Seth still leaned against the mossy curb, smoking
      and talking over the words of their elder brother, who sometime before had
      gone in to avoid the dew-fall.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder if we <i>have</i> misjudged him, after all,&rdquo; said Seth. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m
      almost ashamed to accept his favors, after the way I pitched into him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wonder what his scheme really is,&rdquo; mused the more experienced village
      editor.
    </p>
    <p>
