    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER IX.&mdash;AT &ldquo;M&rsquo;TILDY&rsquo;s&rdquo; BEDSIDE.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">L</span>emuel Fairchild
      sat still, smoking his wooden pipe, and looking absently, straight ahead,
      into the papered wall. This habit of gazing at nothing was familiar to
      them all, and when, at Isabel&rsquo;s suggestion, the three young people started
      for a stroll through the orchard path, they left him entirely without
      ceremony. This was growing to be the rule; no one in the family now
      consulted him, or took the trouble to be polite to him. He seemed to have
      become in his own house merely an article of animated furniture, of not
      much more importance than the rough-furred sickly old cat who dozed his
      life away back of the stove.
    </p>
    <p>
      He sat thus in solitude for some time, blankly studying the grotesque
      patterns in the old-fashioned wall-paper, and drawing mechanically at the
      pipe in his mouth, unconscious that no smoke came. Thus Miss Sabrina found
      him when, after a more than ordinarily sharp passage at arms with Alvira,
      she returned from the Kitchen.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I swaow! thet girl gits wuss tempered &rsquo;n&rsquo; more presumin&rsquo; ev&rsquo;ry day
      o&rsquo; her life,&rdquo; she exclaimed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who&mdash;Annie?&rdquo; asked her brother, rousing himself as if from a nap.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Annie! nao! who&rsquo;s talkin&rsquo; abaout <i>her?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh nothin&rsquo;, unly I was thinkin&rsquo; &rsquo;baout Annie&mdash;&lsquo;baout her &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      Seth, yeh knaow,&rdquo; answered Lemuel, apologetically.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what abaout &rsquo;em?&rdquo; The query was distinctly aggressive in
      tone.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, nothin&rsquo; much. I was sort o&rsquo; thinkin&rsquo;&mdash;well, <i>you</i> knaow
      S&rsquo;briny, haow Sissly used to lot on their makin&rsquo; a match of it&mdash;&rsquo;n&rsquo;
      I was kine o&rsquo; wond&rsquo;rin&rsquo; ef this here notion o&rsquo; Seth&rsquo;s goin&rsquo; away wouldn&rsquo;t
      knock it all in th&rsquo; head.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well?&rdquo; Miss Sabrina&rsquo;s monosyllabic comment had so little of sympathy or
      acquiescence in it, that Lemuel continued in an injured tone and with more
      animation, not to say resolution:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I&rsquo;ve hed kine of an idea o&rsquo; goin&rsquo; over &rsquo;n&rsquo; talkin&rsquo; it over
      with M&rsquo;tildy. Mebbe that&rsquo;ll be the best thing to dew.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh <i>you</i> think so, dew yeh? Thet&rsquo;s all th&rsquo; pride <i>you&rsquo;ve</i> got
      lef&rsquo;, is it? I think I see <i>my</i>self goin&rsquo; hangin&rsquo; raound Matildy
      Warren, beggin&rsquo; her to let her granddaughter marry a Fairchild! I&rsquo;m
      ashamed of yeh, Lemuel.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo; see, much, what ther&rsquo; is to be ashamed on.&rdquo; He added, with the
      faintest shadow of a grin on his face. &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; b&rsquo;twixt you &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      me, I don&rsquo;t see &rsquo;s there&rsquo;s so blamed much fur me to be praoud
      abaout, nuther. &lsquo;Tain&rsquo;t&rsquo;s if I was goin&rsquo; to ask a favor o&rsquo; M&rsquo;tildy, at
      all. She &rsquo;n&rsquo; Sissly used to talk &lsquo;baout the thing&rsquo;s if &rsquo;twas
      settled. &rsquo;N&rsquo; now&rsquo;t she&rsquo;s gone, &rsquo;n&rsquo; Seth&rsquo;s talkin&rsquo; o&rsquo;
      quittin&rsquo; th&rsquo; farm, seems to me it&rsquo;d be the sensible thing to kind o&rsquo; fine
      aout ef M&rsquo;tildy wouldn&rsquo;t offer th&rsquo; young folks her farm, ef they&rsquo;d stay.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Very</i> well, sir. Hev&rsquo; yer own way,&rdquo; answered Miss Sabrina, with
      stern formality. &ldquo;You allus <i>would</i> hev yer own way&mdash;and yeh kin
      go muddle things up to yer heart&rsquo;s content, for all o&rsquo; me!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lemuel watched his sister march to the stairs door and close it decisively
      behind her. He was accustomed of old to this proof of her wrath; as far
      back as he could remember it had been Sabrina&rsquo;s habit to figuratively wash
      her hands of unpleasant complications on the ground-floor by slamming this
      self-same door, and going up to sulk in her own room. She did it as a
      young girl, in the first months of her disagreements with his young wife;
      it seemed to him a most natural proceeding now, when they were both old,
      gray-headed people.
    </p>
    <p>
      Just now, it was a relief to him that she had gone, for if she had stayed
      he might not have had the courage to put his thoughts into actions. As it
      was he took his hat from its nail back of the kitchen door, and started
      across-lots for the Warren homestead.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      There was no danger of not finding Mrs. Warren at home. For seven or eight
      years she had scarcely stirred beyond her own door, and for the past
      eighteen months she had been bed-ridden. The front door was opened to Mr.
      Fairchild by a young slip of a girl, one of the brood of daughters with
      which a neighboring poor family was weighted down, and all of whom had
      been driven to seek work at any price among the farmers of the vicinity.
      It seemed as if there was a Lawton girl in every other farmhouse the whole
      length of the Burfield road.
    </p>
    <p>
      The girl ushered him into the gloomy hall, gloomier than ever now in the
      gathering twilight, and unceremoniously left him there, while she went to
      announce his presence. He heard through a door ajar at the end of the hall
      a thin, querulous voice ask, &ldquo;Which one of the Fairchilds is it?&rdquo; and the
      girl&rsquo;s reply &ldquo;The old man.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Then the servant returned to him and with a curt &ldquo;Come ahead,&rdquo; led him to
      the mistress of the house, who lay in her bed-home, in a recess off the
      living room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Matilda Warren had never been what might be called a popular woman in
      the neighborhood. She and her husband, the latter dead now for many years,
      had come from Massachusetts. They were educated people in a sense, and had
      not mingled easily with their rougher neighbors. The widow Warren had,
      after her daughter&rsquo;s escapade, carried this exclusiveness to a point which
      the neighborhood found disagreeable. Gradually she had grown into the
      recluse habit, and younger generations on the hillside, eking out the
      gossip of their elders with fancies of their own, born of stray glimpses
      of her tall, gaunt figure and pale face, came to regard her with much that
      same awe which, two centuries before, reputed witches had for children,
      young and old.
    </p>
    <p>
      Something of this feeling Lemuel himself was conscious of, as he stood
      before her. The coverlet came up close under her arms. She wore a
      wrapper-dress of red flannel. As he entered she raised herself, with an
      evidently cruel effort, upon her elbow, dragging the pillow down to aid in
      supporting her shoulder. She panted with this exertion as she confronted
      him. Her scanty white hair was combed tightly back from her forehead, and
      bound in place with a black-velvet band; a natural parting on the side of
      the hair gave the withered face a suggestion of juvenile jauntiness, in
      grotesque, jarring contrast with the pale blue eyes which glittered from
      caverns of dark wrinkles, and the sunken, distorted mouth. She had changed
      so vastly since their last meeting that Lemuel stood bewildered and
      silent, staring at her.
    </p>
    <p>
      She spoke first. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m trying to think&mdash;it must be twenty year since
      we&rsquo;ve met, Lemuel Fairchild.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Nigh onto that, M&rsquo;tildy,&rdquo; he replied, turning his hat in his hands.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t expect ever to lay eyes on you again, I couldn&rsquo;t come to you,
      and wouldn&rsquo;t if I could, and I didn&rsquo;t dream you would ever show your face
      here.&rdquo; The aged woman said this in a high, sharp voice, speaking rapidly
      and with an ungracious tone.
    </p>
    <p>
      Lemuel fidgetted with his hat and moved his feet uneasily on the dog-skin
      rug. &ldquo;Yeh needn&rsquo;t be afeered, M&rsquo;tildy, I wouldn&rsquo;t hev come naow ef it
      hadn&rsquo;t been somethin&rsquo; partikler &rsquo;baout Annie.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The invalid raised her shoulder from the pillow with a sudden movement,
      and bent her head forward. &ldquo;What&rsquo;s happened to her? Is she hurt? Tell me,
      quick!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh nao, they ain&rsquo;t nothin&rsquo; th&rsquo; matter with her. It&rsquo;s unly &rsquo;baout
      her &rsquo;n&rsquo; Seth. I kine o&rsquo; thought we ought to talk it over &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      see haow the land lay. That&rsquo;s all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh that&rsquo;s it, is it? <i>Samantha!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Betrayed out of her shrewdness by the suddenness of the summons the
      servant girl made her immediate appearance through the hall door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I knew you were listening, you huzzy,&rdquo; said Mrs. Warren grimly. &ldquo;You
      get along up stairs, go into Annie&rsquo;s room, an&rsquo; make a noise of some sort
      on the melodeon till I call you. Not too much noise, mind; jest enough so
      I can know you&rsquo;re up there.&rdquo; As the girl left the room, the invalid
      explained: &ldquo;What she don&rsquo;t hear, the rest of the Lawtons won&rsquo;t know. That
      family&rsquo;s as good as a detective force for the whole county.&rdquo; Then, in a
      less amiable tone: &ldquo;You might as well set down. What is it about my girl
      an&rsquo; Seth?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      As Lemuel awkwardly seated himself near the bedside and prepared to
      answer, a wailing, discordant series of sounds came from the floor above.
      The knowledge that the girl was creating this melancholy noise to order,
      and on his account, confused his thought and he found himself stating the
      case much more baldly than he had intended. &ldquo;The fact is,&rdquo; he said,
      stroking his hat over his knee, &ldquo;Seth&rsquo;s thinkin&rsquo; o&rsquo; goin&rsquo; away to Tecumsy&mdash;Albert&rsquo;s
      got him a place there&mdash;&rsquo;n&rsquo; so I s&rsquo;pose it&rsquo;ll be all up b&rsquo;twixt
      him &rsquo;n&rsquo; Annie.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The grandmother never took those light, searching eyes off her visitor&rsquo;s
      face. He felt himself turning uncomfortably red under their malevolent
      gaze, I and wished she would speak. But she said nothing. At last he
      explained, deferentially:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought it&rsquo;d only be right to tell yeh. I know Sissly &rsquo;n&rsquo; you
      use to talk abaout th&rsquo; thing. Th&rsquo; way she use to talk, speshly jis&rsquo; &rsquo;fore
      she died, it &rsquo;peared &lsquo;s if you tew hed it all settled. But Albert&rsquo;s
      goin&rsquo; to take th&rsquo; farm, it seems, &rsquo;n&rsquo; Seth, he&rsquo;s fig&rsquo;rin&rsquo; on goin&rsquo;
      away to be a neditor, &rsquo;n&rsquo; it looks to me&rsquo;s if th&rsquo; hull plan&rsquo;d fell
      threw.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Still no reply from the bed. He added, helplessly &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t it kind o&rsquo; seem
      so to you, M&rsquo;tildy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The wretched discords from the chamber above mocked him. The witch-like
      eyes from the shadows of the recess began to burn him. It was growing into
      the dusk, but the eyes had a light of their own, a cold, steely, fierce
      light. Would she never speak? How he regretted having come!
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll tell you what seems to me, Lemuel Fairchild,&rdquo; she said at last, not
      speaking so rapidly now, and putting a sharp, finishing edge on each of
      her words. &ldquo;It seems to me that there&rsquo;s never been but one decent,
      honorable, likely human bein&rsquo; in your whole family an&rsquo; she came into it by
      the mistake of marrying you. I blame myself for not remembering the blood
      that was in you all, an&rsquo; for thinking that this youngest son of yours was
      different from the rest. I forgot that he was a Fairchild like the others,
      an&rsquo; I forgot what I owed that family of men, so mean and cowardly and
      selfish that they have to watch each other like so many hyenas. An&rsquo; so
      you&rsquo;ve come to tell me that Seth has turned out like his father, like his
      uncle, like all of his name, eh? The more fool I, to need to be told it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lemuel&rsquo;s impulse was to rise from his chair, and bear himself with
      offended dignity, but the glitter in the old woman&rsquo;s eyes warned him that
      the attempt would be a failure. He scowled, put his hat on the other knee,
      crossed his legs, pretended to be interested in the antics of a kitten
      which was working havoc with a ball of yarn at his feet. Finally he said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You ain&rsquo;t fair to Seth. He&rsquo;s a good boy. He ain&rsquo;t said nothin&rsquo; nor done
      nothin&rsquo; fer yeh to git mad at. Fer that matter, you never was fair to any
      of us, &rsquo;cept Sissly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Fair! <i>Fair!</i>&rdquo; came the answer promptly, and in a swifter measure.
      &ldquo;Hear the man! Why, Lemuel Fairchild, you know that you cheated your own
      brother out of the share in that farm that was his by all rights as much
      as yours. You <i>know</i> that your father intended you both to share
      alike, that he died too suddenly to make a new will and that you grabbed
      everything under a will made when your brother William was thought to be
      too sickly to ever raise. You <i>know</i> that you let him grow up an
      idle, worthless coot of a fellow, an&rsquo; then encouraged him&mdash;yes, don&rsquo;t
      deny it, encouraged him I say&mdash;to make a fool of my daughter, and run
      away with her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You knew I wouldn&rsquo;t look at him as a suitor for Jenny; but you thought I
      would be soft enough, once they were married, to give him my farm, an&rsquo; you
      counted on getting it away from him afterwards, just as your father got
      the Kennard farm before you. You egged him on into the trouble, an&rsquo; you
      let him die in it, without help. Oh <i>I</i> know you, Lemuel Fairchild&mdash;I
      know your breed!
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Your <i>wife</i> was a good woman&mdash;a million times better than you
      deserved. <i>She</i> knew the wrongs that had been done me, an&rsquo; Annie, an&rsquo;
      her poor ne&rsquo;er-do-well of a father before her; <i>she</i> was anxious to
      make them good, not I. It was she who talked, year after year, when she
      ran over here on the sly to visit me, of squaring everything by the young
      folk&rsquo;s marriage. For a long time I didn&rsquo;t like it. I distrusted the
      family, as, God knows, I had reason to. But all that I heard of Seth was
      in his favor. He was hardworking, patient, even-tempered, so everyone
      said. What little I saw of him I liked. An&rsquo; I felt sorry for him, too,
      knowing how dear he was to his mother, and yet how helpless she was to
      give him advantages, an&rsquo; make something besides a farm-drudge out of him.
      So little by little, I gave in to the idea, an&rsquo; finally it became mine
      almost as much as Cecily&rsquo;s.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;As for Annie, I don&rsquo;t know how much she has grown to care for him; I&rsquo;m
      afraid she&rsquo;s known about our talks, and lotted on &rsquo;em, though if
      anything has passed between them she would have told me. For she&rsquo;s a good
      girl&mdash;a <i>good</i> girl&mdash;and she&rsquo;ll stand by me, never fear,
      and say as I say now, that it&rsquo;s good riddance! D&rsquo;ye mind? Good riddance to
      bad rubbish&mdash;to your whole miserable, conniving, underhanded family!
      There ain&rsquo;t an honest hair in your head, Lemuel Fairchild, and there never
      was. And you can go back to them that sent you, to your old catamaran of a
      sister and your young sneak of a son, and tell &rsquo;em what I think of
      them, and you, and the whole caboodle of you, that ruined and killed my
      Jane, and made me a broken old woman before my time, and now tries to
      break my grand-daughter&rsquo;s heart! And the longest day you Jive, don&rsquo;t ever
      let me lay eyes on you again. That&rsquo;s all!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Lemuel groped his way out again through the dark hall, to the front door.
      The groaning discords from upstairs rose to a triumphant babel of sound as
      he knocked against the hat-rack, and fumbled for the latch, as if to
      emphasize and gloat over his discomfiture. The cold evening air, after the
      sweltering heat of the sick-room, was a physical relief, but it brought no
      moral comfort.
    </p>
    <p>
      Old Lemuel was much pained, and even more confused, by the hard words to
      which he had had to listen. They presented a portrait of himself which he
      felt to be in no way a likeness, yet he could not say wherein a single
      line should be altered. He knew that he was not a bad man; he felt
      conscious of having done no special wrong, intentionally, to anybody; he
      had always tried to be fair and square and easy-going with everybody: yet
      the mischief of it was that all these evil things which the witchlike
      M&rsquo;tildy had piled at his door were of indubitable substance, and he could
      not prove, even to himself, much less to her, that they did not belong
      there. It was a part of the consistently vile luck of his life that all
      these malignant happenings should be charged up against him, and used to
      demonstrate his wickedness. He had not enough mental skill or alertness to
      sift the unfair from the true in the indictment she had drawn, or to put
      himself logically in her place, and thus trace her mistakes. He only
      realized that all these events which she enumerated had served to convince
      Mrs. Warren that he was a villain. The idea was a new one to him, and it
      both surprised and troubled him to find that, as he thought the matter
      over he could not see where she was particularly wrong. Yet a villain he
      had certainly never intended to be&mdash;never for a moment. Was this not
      cruelly hard luck?
    </p>
    <p>
      And then there was this business about Seth. He had meant it all in the
      friendliest spirit, all with the best of motives. And how she had snapped
      him up before he had a chance to explain, and called him a scoundrel and
      his boy a sneak, and driven him from the house! Here was a muddle for one&mdash;and
      Sabrina had said he would make a muddle of it, as he had of everything
      else, all through his life. The lonely, puzzled, discouraged old man felt
      wofully like shedding tears, as he approached his own gate&mdash;or no, it
      was Albert&rsquo;s gate now&mdash;and passed the young people chatting there,
      and realized what a feeble old fool they all must think him.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
