    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXI.&mdash;THE NIGHT: MASTER AND MAN.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">A</span>LBERT walked
      across the yard toward the larger of the new stable buildings. It was a
      dry, warm, luminous night, radiant overhead with the glory of a whole
      studded heaven of stars. The moon, the full, shining-faced moon of
      October, would rise in an hour or so, and then would come pale mists along
      the valley bottom-lands, and perhaps clouds in the eastern sky. But one
      could walk bareheaded in this soft starlight now, without a fear of cold.
    </p>
    <p>
      The lawyer paid no sort of attention to the night, but strode across the
      grass, swung himself over the stile, and pulled back the great stable
      door, creaking shrilly on its rollers, with angry energy. He stopped upon
      the threshold of the darkness, through which the shapes of carriages
      covered with white sheets vaguely loomed, and called out:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Milton!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was the answering sound of footsteps overhead. A door at the top of
      the stairs was opened, and a flood of light illumined the staircase.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you&rsquo;ve got back, ay?&rdquo; said a voice from the top.
    </p>
    <p>
      It had been Milton&rsquo;s idea, when the new buildings were erected, to achieve
      complete domestic autonomy by arranging for himself a residential room
      above the carriage place. The chamber was high and commodious. It had been
      lathed and plastered, and, in lieu of wall-paper, the sides were decorated
      with coarsely-colored circus bills, or pictures from sporting weeklies,
      all depicting women in tights. There was a good corded bed in one corner.
      Two chairs, a stained pine table on which, beside the lamp, were some
      newspapers, a little wood stove, and a mantel-shelf covered with tin-types
      and cheap photographs, completed the scene. Milton enjoyed living here
      greatly. It comported with his budding ideas of his own personal dignity,
      and it freed him from the disagreeable supervision which the elder Miss
      Fairchild was so prone to exercise over all who lived in the house. Only
      the Lawton girl, Melissa, came across the yard each forenoon, to tidy up
      the room, and chuckle over the pictures and the tastes which these, and
      the few books Milton from time to time brought home from a
      sporting-library at Thessaly, indicated.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s lucky you hadn&rsquo;t gone to bed,&rdquo; said the lawyer, curtly, pulling his
      hat over his eyes to shade them from the flaring light, and sitting down.
      &ldquo;I was going to wake you up. What&rsquo;s your news?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been over to Tyre twice to see Beekman, &rsquo;n&rsquo; no use. Once he
      wouldn&rsquo;t talk at all&mdash;jis&rsquo; kep his ole lantern-jaws tight shet, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      said &rsquo;Ef Albert Fairchild wants to see me, he knaows where I kin be
      faound.&rsquo; Th&rsquo; other time he was more talkative&mdash;tried his best to fine
      aout what I was drivin&rsquo; at, but I couldn&rsquo;t git no satisfaction aout o&rsquo;
      him. He wouldn&rsquo;t bine himself to nothin&rsquo;. He jis&rsquo; stood off et arm&rsquo;s
      lenth, &rsquo;n&rsquo; sized up what I was a sayin&rsquo; in that dum sly way o&rsquo; his.
      I couldn&rsquo;t make head nor tail of him. He wouldn&rsquo;t say he would take money,
      &rsquo;n&rsquo; he wouldn&rsquo;t say he wouldn&rsquo;t. He wouldn&rsquo;t say yes or nao to th&rsquo;
      post office scheme, or anythin&rsquo; else. He jis&rsquo; kep&rsquo; his big eyes on me, as
      much as to say, &lsquo;You ketch a weasel asleep!&rsquo; &rsquo;n&rsquo; listened. Naow yeh
      knaow th&rsquo; hull of it. If yeh want anythin&rsquo; more done, yeh better do it
      yerself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The lawyer looked attentively at his hired man, and drummed with his
      fingers on the-table. &ldquo;So that&rsquo;s all, is it? You are no further ahead with
      Beek-man than when the Convention adjourned? You&rsquo;ve got no proposition
      from him&mdash;no statement as to how he takes my proposals?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s it, Albert&mdash;jest it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Something in Milton&rsquo;s tone seemed to annoy Albert even more than his
      confession of failure had done. He rose to his feet abruptly. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t
      &lsquo;Albert&rsquo; me!&rdquo; he said, raising his voice out of its accustomed calm; &ldquo;I
      don&rsquo;t like it! You take too much upon yourself. But&mdash;I am to blame
      for it myself. I&rsquo;ve let you run things with too free a hand, and trusted
      affairs to you that I ought to have kept to myself. It is always my way,&rdquo;
       he went on, in petulant selfcriticism. &ldquo;I never did trust anybody who was
      worth the powder to blow him up. I ought to be used to it by this time.
      But to encounter two such fools in one evening&mdash;and this evening of
      all others, too&mdash;by George! it&rsquo;s enough to make a man strike his
      mother!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I ain&rsquo;t no fool, Mister Fairchild&rdquo;&mdash;the hired man was standing up
      too, and his harsh tones gave the title an elaborate, almost ridiculous
      emphasis&mdash;&ldquo;&rsquo;n&rsquo; I&rsquo;ll thank yeh to keep yer tongue civil, tew!
      Ef yeh don&rsquo;t like my style, yeh kin git sum&rsquo;un else to do yer dirty work
      for yeh. I&rsquo;ve no hankerin&rsquo; fer it. I&rsquo;m hired to manage this farm, I am.
      Nothin&rsquo; was said &rsquo;baout my hevin&rsquo; to run a Congresshn&rsquo;l campaign
      into th&rsquo; bargain. I ain&rsquo;t sayin&rsquo; but what I kin do it&rsquo;s well&rsquo;s some other
      folks. I ain&rsquo;t sayin&rsquo; that it&rsquo;s beyon&rsquo; me. P&rsquo;raps I&rsquo;ve got my pull &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      this caounty, &rsquo;s well &rsquo;s some other people. P&rsquo;raps &rsquo;f
      I was amine to, I could knock somebuddy&rsquo;s game skyhigh, jis&rsquo; by liftin&rsquo; my
      little finger tomorrer. I ain&rsquo;t sayin&rsquo; I&rsquo;m goin&rsquo; to dew it. I ain&rsquo;t
      findin&rsquo; no fault with yeh. All I say is I ain&rsquo;t goin&rsquo; to take one ioty o&rsquo;
      slack from you, or anybody else, about this thing. You hear <i>me!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The hired man had spoken aggressively and loudly, with his thumbs in the
      arm-holes of his vest, and his shaggy head well up in the air. He knew his
      employer pretty well, and had estimated with some precision the amount of
      impudence he would bear. This full measure he was not disposed to abate
      one atom. He had failed to buy the Jay County boss, or even to
      satisfactorily gauge his intentions, it was true, but that was no reason
      why he should submit to being called a fool by Albert Fairchild, who
      couldn&rsquo;t run his farm, let alone his Congressional campaign, without him.
      So the mean-figured, slouching countryman, with his cheap, ill-fitting
      clothes, frowzy beard, and rough, red hands truculently spread palm
      outward on his breast, stood his ground before the city lawyer and grinned
      defiance at him.
    </p>
    <p>
      The lawyer did not immediately reply. He was not ordinarily at a loss for
      words or decisions in his dealings with men, but this rude, uncouth
      rustic, with his confident air and his fund of primordial cunning, puzzled
      him. There was some uneasiness in the feeling, too, for he could not
      remember the exact limits of his confidences with Milton. Moreover he
      could not afford, at any price, to quarrel with him now on the eve of the
      Convention. &ldquo;After the election we&rsquo;ll clip your wings, my fine fellow,&rdquo; he
      thought to himself, but he gave the words upon which he finally decided a
      kindlier turn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I hear you. Almost anybody on the side-hill could, the way you are
      talking. There is no reason why you should lose your temper. If you
      couldn&rsquo;t fix Beekman, why that&rsquo;s all there is to it. We must go at it in a
      different way. I can see through him. He&rsquo;s standing out for a cash
      payment. The old fox wants money down.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you&rsquo;ve got it fur him, hain&rsquo;t yeh? Go &rsquo;n&rsquo; give it to him,
      straight aout!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But that&rsquo;s it&mdash;I wanted you to bring back an idea of his figure.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;His figger. How much hev yeh got?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never mind that&mdash;it&rsquo;s a d&mdash;&mdash;d sight more than the office
      is worth; but when a man gets into a fight of this sort, he&rsquo;s got to force
      his way through, cost or no cost.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Air yeh sure it can&rsquo;t be traced? Wuz yeh careful to raise it so nobuddy
      cud spot yeh, and give aout that yeh got so much money together for
      purposes o&rsquo; bribery?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, it is perfectly safe. There is no record.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; nobuddy on airth knaows yeh&rsquo;ve got th&rsquo; money?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not a living soul!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The two men communed together as to the importance of immediate action.
      The Convention was to reassemble at Tyre, fifteen miles away, at eleven
      the following forenoon. The political master of Jay County, Abe Beekman,
      who held in his hands the deciding power, lived near Tyre, but in the
      valley some miles further on. The first train from Thessaly in the morning
      would be too late, for Beekman would have already arrived on the ground at
      Tyre, coming from the opposite direction, and would have begun work on his
      own hook. He must be seen at his home, early in the morning. The question
      was&mdash;how to encompass this.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You might drive across to-night,&rdquo; Albert suggested; &ldquo;it can&rsquo;t be more
      than twenty miles. It&rsquo;s a bad, up-hill road, but four or five hours ought
      to do it, easily enough. By George&mdash;I believe I&rsquo;ll go myself&mdash;start
      at once, see Beekman about daybreak, and then come back to Tyre by
      breakfast time; as if I had just driven over from here. No one will
      suspect a thing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, thet&rsquo;s a fust-rate idee,&rdquo; assented Milton; &ldquo;only be keerful &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      put yer money in a safe place.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The lawyer again slapped his breast with a confident &ldquo;Never fear about
      that,&rdquo; and went to the house to get some wraps for the night ride, leaving
      Milton to harness the grays, and drag out the sidebar buggy with the pole.
      The hired-man hummed to himself as he moved quietly, dextrously in the
      semi-darkness in the performance of this task.
    </p>
    <p>
      Albert returned, just as the hame straps were being buckled.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Everybody seems to be asleep in the house,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;If they ask any
      questions in the morning, mind you know nothing whatever. That brother of
      mine is no friend. Be careful what you say to him. Let him walk to the
      depot in the morning. It&rsquo;ll do him good. Oh yes, by the way, better let me
      have one of those revolvers of yours&mdash;you have &rsquo;em upstairs,
      haven&rsquo;t you&mdash;give me the one that strikes fire every time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Milton came down and out presently, saying that he just remembered having
      lent the weapon. &ldquo;&rsquo;Tother&rsquo;s no good,&rdquo; he added; &ldquo;yeh don&rsquo;t need no
      pistol anyway. Th&rsquo; moon&rsquo;ll be up direc&rsquo;ly.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Albert gathered up the lines, and drove out slowly toward the road.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yeh better save th&rsquo; beasts till after yeh git over Tallman&rsquo;s hill, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      rest &rsquo;em there by th&rsquo; gulf!&rdquo; Milton called after him, as a last
      injunction.
    </p>
    <p>
      The hired man stood at the stable door, and watched the buggy pass the
      darkened, silent house, turn out on the high-road, and disappear beneath
      the poplars. The moon was just coming up, beyond this line of trees, and
      it made the gloom of their shadow deeper. His eyes, from following the
      vehicle ranged back to the house, which reared itself black against the
      whitening sky. There was there no sound, nor any sign of life. He took a
      revolver out of his pocket, and examined it in the starlight, cocking it
      again and again to make sure that there had been no mistake. Satisfied
      with the inspection, he put it back in his side coat-pocket. He went
      upstairs, changed his hat, took a drink out of a flat brown bottle in his
      cupboard, and spent a minute or two looking at one of the tin-type
      portraits on the mantel-shelf. He held the picture to the light, and
      grinned as he gazed&mdash;then put it in his breast pocket, blew out the
      lamp, and felt his way softly down stairs.
    </p>
    <p>
      A few minutes later he came out from the stable, leading the swift black
      mare. She was saddled and bridled, and seemed to understand, as he led her
      over the grass, that he wanted no noise made. The man and beast, throwing
      long, grotesque shadows on the lawn, in the light of the low moon, stole
      past the house, and out upon the road. Milton here climbed into the
      saddle, and with an exultant little cluck, started in the direction his
      master had gone, still keeping the black mare on the grass. They, too,
      disappeared under the poplars.
    </p>
    <p>
      The moon mounted into the heavens, pushing aside the aspiring clouds which
      sought to dispute her passage, then clothing them in her own livery of
      light, and drawing them upward after her, in a glittering train of
      attendance. All over the hill-side the calm radiance rested. The gay hues
      with which autumn&rsquo;s day brush painted the woods, the hedge rows, the long
      stretches of orchard, stubble, and field, sought now to only hint at their
      beauty, as they yielded new outlines, mystic suggestions of form and
      color, in the soft gray picture of mezzotint. Thin films of vapor rose to
      enwrap the feet of the dark firs, nearer to the sky, and in the valley
      below the silver of the moonlight lost itself on the frost-like whiteness
      of the gathering mist. It was a night for the young to walk together, and
      read love&rsquo;s purest, happiest thoughts in each other&rsquo;s eyes&mdash;for the
      old to drink in with thankful confession the faith that the world was
      still gracious and good.
    </p>
    <p>
      Milton was walking the mare now, still on the grass. He could hear the
      sound of wheels, just ahead.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
