    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXVIII.&mdash;BETWEEN THE BREAD-PAN AND THE CHURN.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">W</span>ELL, I don&rsquo; knaow
      &rsquo;s I go&rsquo;s fur&rsquo;s Sabriny, &rsquo;n&rsquo; say ther&rsquo;s a cuss on th&rsquo;
      fam&rsquo;ly, &rsquo;n&rsquo; thet M&rsquo;tildy Warren put it there, fur after all, three
      deaths hand-runnin&rsquo; in tew years ain&rsquo;t an onheerd-of thing, but I don&rsquo;t
      blame her fur gittin&rsquo; daown-hearted over it. Poor ole creetur, she&rsquo;s be&rsquo;n
      a carryin&rsquo; the hull load o&rsquo; grief on her shoulders sence Sissly died. I
      shouldn&rsquo;t wonder if it&rsquo;d be tew much for her naow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Alvira sighed, and let her eyes wander compassionately from the kneading
      board and its batch of dough to the old, cushioned arm chair by the
      kitchen stove where Aunt Sabrina customarily sat. This last bereavement
      had rendered the hired-girl almost sentimental in her attitude toward the
      stricken old maid&mdash;so much so that when young Samantha Lawton dropped
      in, toward evening, and offered to sit down in this chair, Alvira had
      sharply warned her to take another.
    </p>
    <p>
      The girl had brought a note over from Annie to Seth, and was not a little
      vexed that Alvira should have taken it from her, and gone upstairs to
      deliver it herself, instead of allowing the messenger to complete her
      errand. She declined, therefore, to display any interest in the subject of
      the aged aunt, and warmed her hands over the glowing stove-griddles in
      silence. The elder Lawton girl, Melissa, resting for a moment from her
      churning, turned the talk into a more personal channel.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Fur <i>my</i> part, I think it&rsquo;s a pesky shame, where there&rsquo;s three big
      strappin&rsquo; men &rsquo;raoun&rsquo; th&rsquo; haouse, to make a girl wag this old
      chum-dash till her arms are ready to drop off. &rsquo;N&rsquo; I&rsquo;ll tell &rsquo;em
      sao, tew.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I sh&rsquo;d thought Dany&rsquo;d done it fur yeh&rdquo; said her younger sister, with a
      grin. &ldquo;He allus seemed to me to be soft enough to do all yer work fur yeh,
      ef you&rsquo;d let him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not he! Both he &rsquo;n&rsquo; Leander ain&rsquo;t so much&rsquo;s lifted a finger &rsquo;raoun&rsquo;
      th&rsquo; haouse to-day. They&rsquo;re off daown to th&rsquo; corners, hangin&rsquo; raoun&rsquo; th&rsquo;
      store, &rsquo;n&rsquo; swoppin&rsquo; yarns &rsquo;baout th&rsquo; accident. <i>They</i>
      wouldn&rsquo;t keer &rsquo;f I churned away here till I spit blood. In th&rsquo;
      mornin&rsquo; he&rsquo;ll be awful sorry, of course, &rsquo;n&rsquo; swear he furgot all &rsquo;baout
      Wednesday&rsquo;s bein&rsquo; churnin&rsquo; day. Thet&rsquo;s th&rsquo; man of it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; I s&rsquo;pose Milton never does nothin&rsquo; &rsquo;baout th&rsquo; haouse
      naowadays,&rdquo; remarked Samantha, interrogatively.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, siree!&rdquo; snapped Alvira. &ldquo;You bet he daon&rsquo;t! He&rsquo;s tew high &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      mighty fur thet! Prob&rsquo;ly he&rsquo;s furgot so much as th&rsquo; name of a churn, even.
      He might git his broadcloth suit spotted, tew. I wouldn&rsquo;t dream o&rsquo; askin&rsquo;
      <i>him</i>. I&rsquo;d ruther ask Seth any day then I hed Milton. <i>He</i> don&rsquo;t
      put on half so many airs, even if he does git thirty dollars a week in
      Tecumseh, &rsquo;n&rsquo; live &rsquo;mong ladies &rsquo;n&rsquo; gentlemen ev&rsquo;ry
      day &rsquo;f his life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Melissa rested from her labors again, to say sneeringly: &ldquo;Pritty ladies &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      gentlemen he <i>use&rsquo;t</i> to travel with, there in Tecumsy, accordin&rsquo; to
      all accaounts!&rdquo; Alvira paused in turn, with her arms to the elbow in the
      floury mixing, and an angry glitter in her little black eyes. &ldquo;Ef I was <i>some</i>
      folks, &rsquo;n&rsquo; hed <i>some</i> folk&rsquo;s relations in Tecumsy, &rsquo;pears
      to me I&rsquo;d keep my maouth pritty blamed shut &rsquo;baout what goes on
      there!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The retort was ample. There was no answering sound, save the muffled
      splash and thud of Melissa&rsquo;s vigorously-resumed churning.
    </p>
    <p>
      The lull in conversation was beginning to grow oppressive when the young
      visitor asked: &ldquo;Haow does th&rsquo; fine lady take it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She seems more opset than anyone&rsquo;d given her credit fur,&rdquo; Alvira
      answered, sententiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      Melissa interposed to expand this comment, and rest her arms: &ldquo;Yes, she <i>seems</i>
      opset enough. P&rsquo;raps she <i>is</i>. But then agin, p&rsquo;raps ef you was young
      &rsquo;n&rsquo; good lookin&rsquo;, with blew eyes &rsquo;n&rsquo; a lot o&rsquo; yalleh hair
      thet was all yer own, &rsquo;n&rsquo; you hed a hus-ban&rsquo; twice as old as you
      was, &rsquo;n&rsquo; he sh&rsquo;d fall daown &rsquo;n&rsquo; break his neck, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      leave you a rich young widder, p&rsquo;raps you&rsquo;d cry yer eyes aout&mdash;when
      people was lookin&rsquo;&mdash;speshly if thet husban&rsquo; o&rsquo; yours left a likely
      young brother who was soft on yeh. When you git as old &rsquo;s I be,
      S&rsquo;manthy, you&rsquo;ll learn ther&rsquo;s a good deal in appear&rsquo;nces.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When she gits as old as you air,&rdquo; broke in Alvira, sharply, &ldquo;I hope
      she&rsquo;ll learn better &rsquo;n&rsquo; to blab everythin&rsquo; thet comes into her
      head! You&rsquo;ll let that cream break, ef yeh don&rsquo;t look aout!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t b&rsquo;lieve its within an &rsquo;aour o&rsquo; comin&rsquo;&rdquo; said Melissa,
      wearily resuming her task.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, but&mdash;reelly,&rdquo; began Samantha, &ldquo;<i>is</i> Seth&mdash;&mdash;?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never you mind whether Seth is or whether he isn&rsquo;t,&rdquo; answered Alvira. &ldquo;A
      young tadpole of a girl like you&rsquo;s got no business pryin&rsquo; &rsquo;raoun&rsquo;
      older folks&rsquo; affairs. You better go home! M&rsquo;tildy may need yeh. Yer
      sister&rsquo;s got her work to dew, &rsquo;n&rsquo; so &rsquo;ve I.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This plain intimation produced no effect upon Samantha. She continued to
      warm her hands, which were already the hue of a red apple with the heat,
      and remarked: &ldquo;No, she don&rsquo; want me. Annie said I might stay &rsquo;s
      long &rsquo;s I wanted to. She said she wanted to be left alone. She&rsquo;s
      abaout the wuss broke up girl <i>I</i> ever sot eyes on. You ought to see
      the way <i>she</i> takes on, though. I bet the widder ain&rsquo;t a succumstance
      to her. Ef you&rsquo;d seen what <i>I</i> saw, &rsquo;n&rsquo; heern what <i>I</i>
      heerd this afternoon, I guess you&rsquo;d think so tew.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl spoke calmly, with a satisfied conviction that nobody would tell
      her to go home again in a hurry.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What was it?&rdquo; came simultaneously from the kneading-board and the churn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I dunnao,&mdash;I ain&rsquo;t much of a han&rsquo; to blab everythin&rsquo;. A young
      tadpole of a girl like me, yeh knaow, ain&rsquo;t got no business&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come naow! <i>Don&rsquo;t</i> be a <i>fool</i>, S&rsquo;manthy! Ef you&rsquo;ve got
      anythin&rsquo; to say, spit it aout!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Thus adjured by the commanding tones of Alvira, the girl trifled no more,
      but related what she had seen, while hidden behind the thorns. She had a
      talent for description, and made so much of Annie&rsquo;s stony face and strange
      behavior, that she succeeded in producing an effect of mystification upon
      her listeners scarcely second to that under which she, as an involuntary
      spectator, had labored. The success of her recital was not lost upon
      Samantha, as she went on:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Et was after th&rsquo; undertaker&rsquo;s waggin &rsquo;n&rsquo; th&rsquo; men&mdash;some gallus
      lookin&rsquo; young fellers, f&rsquo;m Tecumsey I guess, was amongst &rsquo;em&mdash;et
      was after these&rsquo;d all gone by, thet I heerd her talk. She kind o&rsquo; hid
      herself in th&rsquo; bushes while they was a goin&rsquo; by, &rsquo;n&rsquo; stared at &rsquo;em
      like mad, ez fur&rsquo;s she c&rsquo;d folly &rsquo;em. Then she bust aout&mdash;not
      a-cryin&rsquo; mind yeh, fur she never shed a tear&mdash;but wringin&rsquo; her han&rsquo;s
      &rsquo;n&rsquo; groanin&rsquo; &rsquo;n&rsquo; actin&rsquo; &rsquo;s ef she was goin&rsquo; to faint. I c&rsquo;d
      see her jest ez plain &rsquo;s I kin see you stan&rsquo;in&rsquo; there naow, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      heer her, tew. All to onc&rsquo;t she up &rsquo;n&rsquo; said&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The young girl stopped here in the narrative abruptly, with a fine
      disregard for the consuming interest with which her companions were
      regarding her; she lifted her nose, and drew two or three leisured sniffs.
      Then she bent down at the side of the stove and repeated them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ther&rsquo;s somethin&rsquo; burnin&rsquo; in thet oven,&rdquo; she said at last, confidently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Et&rsquo;s th&rsquo; barley. I knowed S&rsquo;briny&rsquo;d traipse off &rsquo;n&rsquo; leave it. She
      allus does;&rdquo; said Alvira, flinging open the oven door, and dragging out
      with her apron a smoking pan of scorched grain.
    </p>
    <p>
      Through the dense, pungent smudge which temporarily filled the room,
      Samantha was heard to remark with offensive emphasis: &ldquo;We allus drink
      genu-wine coffee over to M&rsquo;tildy&rsquo;s. She&rsquo;s mean enough &rsquo;baout some
      things, but she wouldn&rsquo;t make us swell ourselves aout with no
      barley-wash.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; sao do we here, tew&mdash;all but S&rsquo;briny!&rdquo; retorted Alvira,
      indignantly. &ldquo;She got use&rsquo; to drinkin&rsquo; it in war-times, when yeh couldn&rsquo;t
      git reel coffee fur love n&rsquo;r money, jes&rsquo; ez all th&rsquo; other farm-folks did.
      On&rsquo;y she&rsquo;s more contrary &rsquo;n&rsquo; th&rsquo; rest, &rsquo;n&rsquo; she wouldn&rsquo;t
      drink nothin&rsquo; else naow, not ef yeh poured it into her maouth with a
      funnel. But go on &rsquo;th yer yarn!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Samantha had to cough a little, on account of the smoke, and then it took
      her some moments to collect the thread of her narrative. But at last even
      the spirit of Tantalus could invent no further delay, and she proceeded:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, she didn&rsquo;t say much, fer a fact, but they was business in ev&rsquo;ry
      word she did say. Fust she hollered aout&mdash;right aout, I tell yeh: &lsquo;<i>Et&rsquo;s
      a wicked lie! She&rsquo;s a bad, wicked woman!</i> &rsquo; Then she stopped fer
      awhile &rsquo;n&rsquo; put her han&rsquo;s up to her for&rsquo;id&mdash;like this. Then she
      shuk herself, &rsquo;n&rsquo; commenced to climb back over th&rsquo; stile, but she
      seemed to think better of it, &rsquo;n&rsquo; started fer her own haouse,
      like&rsquo;s ef she was a walkin&rsquo; in her sleep, &rsquo;n&rsquo; a groanin&rsquo; to
      herself: &lsquo;<i>Seth a murd&rsquo;rer! Seth a murd&rsquo;rer!</i>&rsquo; Thet&rsquo;s what I heerd!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl put both feet up on the stove hearth, and tilted her chair back
      in conscious triumph. &ldquo;Got &rsquo;n&rsquo; apple handy?&rdquo; she inquired of
      Alvira, carelessly, in the tone of one whose position in life was assured.
    </p>
    <p>
      To this strange recital, involving such terrible suggestions, there
      succeeded a full minute of silence in the kitchen, broken only by the
      ponderous clucking of the high wooden clock. Alvira and Melissa looked at
      each other dumbly&mdash;each for once willing to forego the first word.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what d&rsquo;yeh say to <i>thet?</i>&rdquo; finally asked Melissa.
    </p>
    <p>
      After some reflection, Alvira answered, &ldquo;I sh&rsquo;d say S&rsquo;manthy was a lyin&rsquo;.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;S&rsquo;elp me die, crisscross, I ain&rsquo;t!&rdquo; protested the girl at the stove:
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve told it all, jest&rsquo;s it happened, straight&rsquo;s a string. Where&rsquo;s yer
      apples?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Alvira meditated again for a moment. Then she said to her subordinate: &ldquo;Go
      down &rsquo;n&rsquo; git that sister o&rsquo; yourn a Spitzenberg&mdash;&rsquo;n&rsquo;
      bring up some cider, yeh might&rsquo;s well, too.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      When Melissa had gone, Alvira went over to the &lsquo;younger girl, and gripped
      her sharply by the shoulder: &ldquo;Look here, you, is what you&rsquo;ve be&rsquo;n tellin&rsquo;
      us here honest? Don&rsquo;t lie to <i>me!</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Honest Injun? Alviry! ev&rsquo;ry word!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Alvira returned to her dough, and slapped it savagely into a huge,
      unnatural pancake. She maintained silence until Melissa had returned, and
      not only supplied her sister&rsquo;s wants, but poured out a cupful of the new
      cider for herself, as a proof of her appreciation of the Lawton family&rsquo;s
      supremacy over the existing crisis. Then Alvira spoke:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t &rsquo;tach th&rsquo; least &rsquo;mportance in th&rsquo; world to what
      S&rsquo;manthy heerd. Annie&rsquo;s a school-teacher, &rsquo;n&rsquo; she&rsquo;s be&rsquo;n workin&rsquo;
      pritty hard, &rsquo;n&rsquo; this thing&rsquo;s kind o&rsquo; opset her&mdash;what with
      tendin&rsquo; to her gran&rsquo;mother, &rsquo;n&rsquo; then this teachin&rsquo;, which is
      narvous, wearin&rsquo; kine o&rsquo; work. Thet&rsquo;s th&rsquo; trewth o&rsquo; th&rsquo; matter. <i>I</i>
      kin un-derstan&rsquo; it. She was jest aout of her senses. But other folks won&rsquo;t
      understan&rsquo; it as I dew. Once a hint gits flyin&rsquo; amongst outsiders, who
      knaows where it&rsquo;ll stop? Naow, girl &rsquo;n&rsquo; woman, I&rsquo;ve be&rsquo;n in this
      haouse twenty year &rsquo;n&rsquo; more. I&rsquo;m more a Fairchild than I&rsquo;m anythin&rsquo;
      else. I remember th&rsquo; man in there&mdash;layin&rsquo; dead in th&rsquo; parlor&mdash;when
      he was a youngster, comin&rsquo; home f&rsquo;m college; I remember Seth when he was a
      baby. I ain&rsquo;t got no folks of my own thet I keer a thaousandth part &lsquo;s
      much abaout, nur owe a thaousandth part &rsquo;s much tew, ez I dew this
      Fairchile fam&rsquo;ly. <i>Well!</i> They&rsquo;ve hed trouble enough, this las&rsquo; tew
      year, &lsquo;thout havin&rsquo; any added onto it by th&rsquo; tattlin&rsquo;, gossipin&rsquo; tongues
      of outsiders. I ain&rsquo;t goin&rsquo; to <i>hev</i> it! D&rsquo;yeh understan&rsquo;! Ef I heer
      s&rsquo; much&rsquo;s a whisper of this yere crazy school-teacher&rsquo;s nonsense reported
      &lsquo;raound, by th&rsquo; Lord above, I&rsquo;ll skin yeh both alive!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who&rsquo;s <i>b&rsquo;en</i> a gossipin&rsquo;?&rdquo; asked Samantha, reproachfully. &ldquo;I
      shouldn&rsquo;t never said a word, ef you hadn&rsquo;t insisted, &rsquo;n&rsquo; called me
      a fool fur holdin&rsquo; my tongue.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I dunnao where you&rsquo;ll gao to when you die, S&rsquo;manthy,&rdquo; said Alvira,
      reflectively. &ldquo;But nao, girls, trewly naow, this mustn&rsquo;t be mentioned. Yeh
      kin see with half &rsquo;n eye what a raow it&rsquo;d stir up. Naow prommus me,
      both o&rsquo; yeh, thet not a word of it shell pass yer lips. Yeh can see fer
      yerself haow foolish it is! Ev&rsquo;rybody knaows he driv off th&rsquo; raoad, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      killed himself &rsquo;n&rsquo; th&rsquo; hosses by th&rsquo; fall. It&rsquo;s ez plain &lsquo;s th&rsquo;
      nose on yer face. Still it&rsquo;s jest sech cases as this thet people git
      talkin&rsquo; abaout, once they&rsquo;re sot goin&rsquo;&mdash;so yeh <i>will</i> promise
      me, won&rsquo;t yeh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They promised.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hon&rsquo;r bright, ye&rsquo;ll never say a word to nao livin&rsquo; soul?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They asseverated solemnly, honor bright, and Samantha had a doughnut as
      well as another cup of cider.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The tiresome butter came at last, and the dough passed into a higher form
      of existence through the fiery ordeal of the oven; supper was laid and
      silently eaten; two neighbors, volunteers for the night-watch with the
      dead, came, and were ushered into the gloomy parlor; while apples, cheese,
      doughnuts and a pitcher of cider were placed on the table outside, for
      their refreshment in the small hours. Night fell upon the farm.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Melissa Lawton stole out-doors as soon as Alvira retired to her room, and
      made her way through the darkness to the barns. As Albert had done on the
      fatal previous evening, she opened the sliding door of the big stable, and
      called up the stairs to Milton. There was no response, and investigation
      showed that he was not in his room, although the lamp was burning dimly.
      The girl stopped long enough to look over the familiar coarse pictures on
      the walls and the shelf, and then crept down the steep stairs again.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she groped her way through the blackness to the stable door she came
      suddenly in contact with a person entering, and felt herself rudely seized
      and pushed back at arms&rsquo; length.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who&rsquo;s here? What d&rsquo;yeh want?&rdquo; demanded a harsh voice, which seemed
      despite its gruffness to betray great trepidation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s me&mdash;M&rsquo;lissy!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come along aout here into the light, so I kin see yeh. What a&rsquo; yeh doin&rsquo;
      here, praowlin&rsquo; &rsquo;raoun&rsquo; &rsquo;n th&rsquo; dark, skeerin&rsquo; people fur?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Lawton girl&rsquo;s native assurance all came back to her as she confronted
      Milton in the dim starlight outside&mdash;which was radiance by contrast
      with the stable&rsquo;s total darkness&mdash;and she grinned satirically at him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;ve got a nerve on you like a maouse, I swaow! You trembled all over
      when yeh tuk holt o&rsquo; me, in there. What was yeh skeert abaout? I wouldn&rsquo;t
      hurt yeh!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wa&rsquo;n&rsquo;t skeert,&rdquo; the man replied, sullenly. &ldquo;What was yeh after
      in there?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was lookin&rsquo; fur you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What fur?&rdquo; The tone was still uneasily suspicious.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I got somethin&rsquo; to tell yeh.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;D&rsquo;yeh knaow, I more&rsquo;n half b&rsquo;lieve this thing wa&rsquo;n&rsquo;t an accident
      at all. What&rsquo;d yeh say &rsquo;f it sh&rsquo;d turn aout to be a murder?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Even in this faint light Melissa could see that Milton was much taken
      aback by the suggestion. He thrust his hands into his pockets, pulled them
      out again, shuffled his feet, stammered, and betrayed by other signs
      general among rustics his surprise.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pshaw&mdash;git aout!&rdquo; he said at last; &ldquo;what nonsense! Of caourse &rsquo;t
      was &rsquo;n accident. Didn&rsquo;t th&rsquo; Cor&rsquo;ner say sao? Daon&rsquo;t ev&rsquo;rybody knaow
      it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Annie Fairchile don&rsquo;t say sao. <i>She</i> don&rsquo;t knaow it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The girl went on to relate the substance of Samantha&rsquo;s revelations, adding
      unconsciously sundry embellishments which tended to throw a clearer light
      upon Seth as the chief figure in the mystery.
    </p>
    <p>
      Milton listened with deep attentiveness. His slow, inefficient brain
      worked hard to keep up with the recital, and assimilate its chief points.
      When the girl had finished he still thought steadily on this strange
      story, with its unforeseen, startling suggestions. Gradually two items
      took shape in his mind as most important: that Annie believed Seth to be
      the criminal, and hence would be estranged from him; and that if by any
      unexpected means people came to suspect foul play, here were the elements
      of a ready-made suspicion against Seth. The first of these was very
      welcome; it would be time enough to think of the other if a discovery were
      made.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What dew I think?&rdquo; he said at last, in response to the girl&rsquo;s repeated
      inquiries. &ldquo;I think thet sister o&rsquo; yourn lied, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I think yeh
      better keep yer maouth, &rsquo;n&rsquo; her&rsquo;n tew, pritty dum shet, ef yeh
      don&rsquo;t want to git into trouble.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0029" id="link2HCH0029"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXIX.&mdash;THE BOSS LOOKS INTO THE MATTER.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">C</span>OUSIN Seth&mdash;<i>There
      are reasons why I cannot come to the house again, even to the funeral; and
      why I shall not see you again during your stay. I think you will
      understand them. If you explain to Aunt Sabrina that I am ill, it will not
      be a falsehood. I have been and am suffering&mdash;terribly. But nobody
      can help me, save by leaving me to myself. I am trying to forget, too,
      everything that was said when we last talked together, and I shall
      succeed. Never fear, I shall succeed. A.</i>
    </p>
    <p>
      It was this note, scrawled in a hand very unlike Miss Annie&rsquo;s customary
      prim, school-teacher&rsquo;s writing, which Samantha had borne over from the
      Warren house. Seth had studied it, perplexedly, for a long time on the
      evening of its arrival. He ruminated now again upon it, as he walked along
      the road toward Thessaly, the following forenoon. The temptation to
      confide the thing to John, who had stayed over night with him at the
      homestead, and now was walking silently by his side toward the village,
      wavered in his mind. Perhaps John could assist him to comprehend it; but
      then, it would be necessary to explain so much to him first. Finally the
      arguments in favor of confession triumphed, and with a &ldquo;Here, old man;
      this is a letter from Annie. I want you to help me guess what it means,&rdquo;
       he made the plunge.
    </p>
    <p>
      John read the note carefully. &ldquo;What was it you talked about on this
      occasion she refers to, and when was it?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It was night before last, <i>the</i> night, and I asked her to marry me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And what was her answer?&mdash;I&rsquo;ll tell you afterward how glad I am to
      hear what you&rsquo;ve just told me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, it wasn&rsquo;t decisive&mdash;but she admitted that it made her very
      happy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you haven&rsquo;t seen her since?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No&mdash;or yes! I did. I met her just for a moment yesterday forenoon,
      as I was starting out from the house after hearing&mdash;the <i>news</i>.
      We only exchanged a word or two, though.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did she seem angry with you then?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not at all!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what can have happened since? Try and think! She has reasons, she
      says, which she thinks you will understand. When a woman says she has
      &lsquo;reasons&rsquo; she means that some mischief-maker has told her something
      disagreeable. Now&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, my God! I see it now!&rdquo; Seth stopped short in the road, and clenched
      his fists.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, what is it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She went into the house, and saw Isabel!&rdquo; Seth continued, as if talking
      to himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has that got to do with it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Seth looked up at his brother with a blanching face, in which fright and
      amazement blended. &ldquo;What is that line of Congreve&rsquo;s about Hell having no
      fury like a woman scorned?&rdquo; he asked mechanically.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was John&rsquo;s turn to stare. Gradually a light began to spread in his
      mind, and make things visible whose existence he had not suspected before.
      &ldquo;Well, you <i>are</i> a simpleton!&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t I know it?&rdquo; was the pained, contrite response.
    </p>
    <p>
      The brothers walked on a few yards in silence. Then John said &ldquo;Of course,
      you needn&rsquo;t tell me any more of this than you want to&mdash;but at least I
      can ask you&mdash;how <i>much</i> of a fool have you made of yourself up
      at the farm?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s hard to say. Just now I&rsquo;m inclined to think that I am the champion
      ass of the world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you&rsquo;re displaying some sense <i>now</i>, anyway. What have you
      done?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I haven&rsquo;t done anything. That&rsquo;s the foolish part of it all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      John stopped in turn, and looked his brother&rsquo;s face attentively over. &ldquo;Go
      on, now,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;and tell me what there is of it. There&rsquo;s no use in my
      butting my brains out against a stone wall, guessing at such an
      inscrutable mess as this seems to be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s hard to tell&mdash;there isn&rsquo;t anything specially <i>to</i> tell. I
      simply got sort of sentimental about Isabel, you know&mdash;she was lonely
      and disappointed in life, and my coming to the farm was about the only
      chance for company she got, and all that&mdash;and then I found the thing
      might go too far and so I stopped it&mdash;and to clinch the thing, asked
      Annie to marry me. That&rsquo;s what there is of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s good as far as it goes. Go on, youngster; out with the rest of
      it!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I tell you that <i>is</i> all.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Humbug! Annie never wrote this letter on the strength of such
      philandering nonsense as that. You say Isabel must have told her
      something. What <i>was</i> that something? Do you know?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes!&rdquo; The answer was so full of despondent pain, that John&rsquo;s sympathy
      rose above his fraternal censariousness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come, my boy,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;you&rsquo;d better make a clean breast of it. It won&rsquo;t
      seem half so bad, once you&rsquo;ve told me. And if I can help you, you know I
      will.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, I <i>will</i> tell you, John. Night before last, Monday night, I
      had hard words with Albert, up at the house. You know how he sent for me,
      insisted on my coming, and what he wanted. Of course I could only say no,
      and we quarreled. Toward the end we raised our voices, and Isabel, who was
      upstairs, overheard us. Just then he began about me and her&mdash;it seems
      he had noticed or heard something&mdash;and she, hearing her name, took it
      for granted the whole quarrel was about her. I went upstairs, and
      presently he drove out of the yard with the grays. I couldn&rsquo;t sleep, I was
      so agitated by the idea of our rupture, and I went out to walk it off. It
      was while I was out that I met Annie and had the talk I have told you
      about. Then I came home, went to bed, and slept till after ten&mdash;long
      after everybody else had heard the news. I heard of it first from Isabel,
      and she&mdash;she&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He came to an abrupt halt. The duty of saying nothing which should
      incriminate the woman rose before him, and fettered his tongue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And she&mdash;what?&rdquo; asked John.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, she somehow got the idea that I had followed Albert out and&mdash;and&mdash;was
      responsible for his death! <i>Now</i>. you have it all!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a long silence. They were nearing the four corners, and walking
      slowly. Finally John, with his eyes on the ground, said: &ldquo;And so that&rsquo;s
      what she has told Annie, you think?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s the only way I can explain the note.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But Annie couldn&rsquo;t possibly believe such a thing as that!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No&mdash;but there&rsquo;s an explanation for that too. Come to think of it, I
      must have said a lot of things to her, that night, which seem now to her
      to fit in with this awful theory. Poor girl! I don&rsquo;t blame her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      John answered, after a pause, &ldquo;There&rsquo;s no use of my saying anything to
      show you what a situation you are in, or to scold you for it. I suppose
      you realize it fully enough. What&rsquo;s more to the purpose, we must consider
      what is to be done. It is safe enough to assume that if Isabel thinks this
      and has said it to one person, either some one else will think it, or she
      will hint about it to another. The thing is too terrible to have even one
      person, even if she were silent as the grave, think about it. The obvious
      thing, I should think, would be to have a postmortem examination.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I thought they always had them at inquests.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, the Coroner can dispense with one if he and the jury agree that it
      isn&rsquo;t necessary. Timms sent me word that he had decided to dispense with
      one, in this case, &lsquo;out of consideration for the feelings of the family.&rsquo;
      That means, of course, that he wants the <i>Banner</i> to help re-elect
      him next year. But now out of &lsquo;consideration for the family&rsquo; we&rsquo;ll have to
      have one. Don&rsquo;t be so down in the mouth about it, boy; it will all come
      right, never fear!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The brothers had reached the solitary building at the corners&mdash;a low,
      dingy store, with its sloping roof turned to the road, and a broad
      platform and steps stretching along its entire front. A horse and vacant
      buggy stood at the hitching-post. John proposed to go in and get some
      cigars, if Turner had any fit to smoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      Their surprise was great at meeting on the steps Mr. Beekman of Jay
      County, who was coming out. After terse salutations had been exchanged,
      Beekman said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lucky you fellows come daown jest ez yeh did. I come over this mornin&rsquo;
      a-purpose to see yeh, &rsquo;n&rsquo; yit I didn&rsquo;t quite like to go up to th&rsquo;
      farm. I&rsquo;ve got ever so many things I want to ask yeh, &rsquo;n&rsquo; say to
      yeh.&rdquo; He led the way over to the farther end of the steps, and, following
      his example of sitting down on the platform, they waited curiously for him
      to proceed:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Fust of all, I was daown to Tecumsy last night, &rsquo;n&rsquo; saw Workman.
      He said you&rdquo;&mdash;turning to Seth&mdash;&ldquo;needn&rsquo;t worry yerself &rsquo;baout
      comin&rsquo; back till yeh was ready. They kin keep th&rsquo; paper runnin&rsquo; for a week
      or sao, while you stay up here &rsquo;n&rsquo; dew yer duty like a Christian.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Seth said he was much obliged, and then asked how it happened that Beekman
      had posted off to Tecumseh&mdash;over seventy miles&mdash;and returned so
      soon.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, there was some things I wanted to see abaout daown there, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      more thet I&rsquo;m interested in keepin&rsquo; an eye on up here. So I kind o&rsquo; humped
      myself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad to see you taking such an interest in Ansdell&rsquo;s campaign,&rdquo; said
      John.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mr. Beekman&rsquo;s gaunt visage relaxed for a second: &ldquo;So yeh calc&rsquo;late <i>thet&rsquo;s</i>
      what I&rsquo;m buzzin&rsquo; &rsquo;raoun&rsquo; th&rsquo; State fur, do yeh? Yeh never&rsquo;s more
      mistaken in yer life. I&rsquo;ve heerd reports circ&rsquo;latin&rsquo; &rsquo;raoun&rsquo; thet
      ther&rsquo;d be an election a fortni&rsquo;t or so from naow, &rsquo;n&rsquo; thet Ansdell
      &rsquo;n&rsquo; I was concerned in it, but yeh can&rsquo;t prove it by <i>us</i>. We
      ain&rsquo;t s&rsquo; much as give a thought to politics sence th&rsquo; Convention ended. <i>We&rsquo;ve</i>
      got somethin&rsquo; else to occupy aour minds with b&rsquo;sides politics. I got a
      telegraph dispatch from him, sent from New York this mornin&rsquo;, thet I want
      to talk to yeh &rsquo;baout presently, but fust&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ansdell in New York?&rdquo; asked Seth, all curiosity-now.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, he went on daown, while I got off at Te-cumsy, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I sh&rsquo;d
      jedge from his telegraph thet he&rsquo;d be&rsquo;n on the go some sence he got there.
      But what I want to ask yeh &rsquo;baout is this: Do yeh knaow haow much
      money yer brother hed on him night &lsquo;fore last, when he was&mdash;when he
      met his death?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The brothers looked at each other, then at, the speaker, &ldquo;No,&rdquo; answered
      Seth, finally. &ldquo;We haven&rsquo;t the least idea. Why do you ask?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll come to that bimeby. Naow next, do you knaow where he was th&rsquo; day
      b&rsquo;fore th&rsquo; Convention?&mdash;thet is, Monday.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I can tell you that. He was in New York. He only got back Monday
      evening.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pre-cisely. Well, naow, do yeh knaow what he went there for?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. Something connected with politics, I suppose, but I can&rsquo;t say for
      certain. He had business there very often, you know.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I knaow. But he hed very special business this last time. Naow look
      at this telegram.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The two took the oblong sheet, and read:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>New York&mdash;Oct. 21. 942 A.M. Unexpectedly easy sailing. Found clue
      to money almost without looking. Fancy now must been sixteen instead ten.
      Hope return to-night. Ansdell</i>.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, still I am in the dark,&rdquo; John said, after reading and re-reading
      the dispatch. &ldquo;What is it all about? I suppose you understand it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m beginnin&rsquo; to see a leetle ways threw th&rsquo; millstone, I think, myself,&rdquo;
       replied Beekman. &ldquo;But it&rsquo;s all so uncert&rsquo;n yit, I don&rsquo;t want to say
      nothin&rsquo; thet I can&rsquo;t back up later on.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Seth too had been busily pondering the dispatch, and he said now, with a
      flushing face: &ldquo;<i>I</i> know what you think! You and Ansdell have got an
      idea there was foul play!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, yes, it ain&rsquo;t much more&rsquo;n an idee, <i>yit</i>;&rdquo; assented Beekman.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you base your idea on?&rdquo; demanded John, full of a nameless,
      growing fright lest there <i>might</i> be something further which Seth&rsquo;s
      confession had not revealed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Jest you wait one day more,&rdquo; said the Boss of Jay County, grimly, &ldquo;one
      day more &rsquo;ll dew. Then I miss my guess ef we ain&rsquo;t in shape to tell
      yeh. Fust of all, there&rsquo;s got to be a post-mortem.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      John&rsquo;s impulse was to say that he and Seth had already agreed upon this,
      but a second thought checked his tongue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; it&rsquo;ll hev to be on th&rsquo; quiet. Everything depends on thet&mdash;on
      keepin&rsquo; it dark. There&rsquo;s some folks might get skeered, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      complicate things, ef it ain&rsquo;t kep&rsquo; mum. &rsquo;N&rsquo; thet&rsquo;s what I wanted
      to ask yeh &rsquo;baout. I&rsquo;ve thought of Dr. Bacon, over at Thessaly, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      Dr. Pierce daown at the Springs. They&rsquo;re both good men, &rsquo;n&rsquo; got
      level heads on &rsquo;em. What d&rsquo;yeh say to them?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve no objection to them in the world, but the Coroner&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I know &rsquo;bout him. He&rsquo;s th&rsquo; blamedest fool in th&rsquo; caounty. Over
      in Jay we wouldn&rsquo;t elect sech a dumb-head to be hog-reeve. But you &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      Ansdell kin fix it with him to-morrow, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I&rsquo;ll drive to-day &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      see both doctors, &rsquo;n&rsquo; put &rsquo;em straight. &rsquo;N&rsquo; naow yeh
      must prommus me, both of yeh, thet yeh won&rsquo;t breathe a word of this to any
      livin&rsquo; soul.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They promised, and he climbed into his buggy, and gathered up the reins.
      &ldquo;Oh, there&rsquo;s one thing more,&rdquo; he said, on reflection. &ldquo;P&rsquo;raps you wonder
      why I&rsquo;m takin&rsquo; so much on myself. I&rsquo;ll tell yeh bimeby. I&rsquo;ve got my
      reasons. I&rsquo;m mixed up in it, more&rsquo;n you&rsquo;d think.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned about, and drove off briskly toward Thessaly. The brothers stood
      in perplexed silence by the roadside for some minutes. There was surely
      enough to think about.
    </p>
    <p>
      At last, with a frank gesture, John stretched his hand out to Seth:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Old boy,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know how this thing is coming out, but we&rsquo;ll
      see it through together. You go down to the office and wait for me. You
      might do some things to fill up the paper this week if you&rsquo;ve got nerve
      enough. I&rsquo;m going back to the farm.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
