    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXI.&mdash;MILTON&rsquo;S ASPIRATIONS.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>he lamps were
      lighted in the little partitioned-off square which served as the editorial
      room of the <i>Banner</i> when John returned. He found Seth weakly
      striving to write something for the editorial page, and in substance laid
      the situation before him. He was not feeling very amiably toward his young
      brother at the moment, and he spoke with cold distinctness. The tone was
      lost upon Seth, who said wearily:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t see that it makes much difference&mdash;her refusing. What good
      would it have done, if she <i>had</i> gone to Annie? She could only tell
      her that she had abandoned such and such ideas. That isn&rsquo;t what counts.
      The fact of importance is that she ever entertained them, that they ever
      existed. To my notion, there&rsquo;s nothing to do but to wait and see what
      comes of Beekman&rsquo;s suspicions. What do you think of them, anyway? I have
      been trying to imagine what he is aiming at, but it puzzles me? What do
      you think?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To tell the truth, I haven&rsquo;t been thinking of that. My mind has been
      occupied with the female aspects of the thing. I&rsquo;m not impatient.
      Evidently Beekman and Ansdell think they have got hold of something. They
      are not the men to go off on a wild-goose chase. Very good: I can wait
      until they are ready to explain. But what I can&rsquo;t wait for&mdash;or bear
      to think about&mdash;is poor Annie, suffering as she must be suffering to
      have written that letter.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I&rsquo;ve thought of that, too, but I&rsquo;m helpless. I can&rsquo;t think of
      anything: I can&rsquo;t do anything.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t seem to be of much use, for a fact,&rdquo; mused the brother. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll
      tell you what I&rsquo;ll do, if you think best. To-morrow afternoon, after I&rsquo;ve
      seen Ansdell, or before that if he doesn&rsquo;t come, I will go over and see
      Annie myself. I can go over to the school-house by the back road, and walk
      home with her. Perhaps by that time, too, I shall have something tangible
      to explain to her. Until then, I suppose she must continue in suspense. It
      is the penance she ought to do, I dare say&mdash;&rdquo; the brother added this
      in mildly sarcastic rebuke&mdash;&ldquo;for the luxury of being in love with
      such a transcendant genius as you are.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Something like an hour before this, Annie had dismissed her classes and
      locked up the school-house for the night. As she did so, she mentally
      wondered if she should ever have the strength to walk home.
    </p>
    <p>
      The day had been one long-drawn out torture from its first waking moments&mdash;indeed
      there seemed to have been nothing but anguish since her interview with
      Isabel the previous day, not even the oblivion of sleep. Her impulse, and
      her grandmother&rsquo;s advice, had been to remain at home; but she had already
      left the school unopened on the fatal Tuesday, in the shock of the news of
      Albert&rsquo;s death: to absent herself a second day might prejudice the
      trustees against her. Besides, the occupation might serve to divert her
      thoughts.
    </p>
    <p>
      Perhaps the trustees were satisfied, she said to herself now, locking the
      door, but there certainly had been no relief in the day&rsquo;s labor. The
      little children had been unwontedly stupid and trying; the older boys,
      some of them almost of her own age, had never before seemed so unruly and
      loutishly impertinent. Even these experiences alone would have availed to
      discourage her; as it was they added the stinging of insects to her great
      heartache. With some organizations, the lesser pain nullifies the other.
      She seemed to have a capacity for suffering, now, which took in, and made
      the most of, every element of agony, great and small. She turned from the
      rusty, squat little old building and began her journey homeward, with
      hanging head and a deadly sense of weakness, physical and spiritual,
      crushing her whole being.
    </p>
    <p>
      Milton Squires had been watching for her appearance for some time, from a
      sheltering ridge of berry-bushes and wall beyond the school, and he
      hurried now to overtake her, clumsily professing surprise at the meeting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I jes happened up this way,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;Dunnao <i>when</i> I be&rsquo;n up here
      on this road b&rsquo;fore. Never dreampt o&rsquo; seein&rsquo; yeou.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She made answer of some sort, as unintelligible and meaningless to herself
      as to him. She did not know whether it was a relief or otherwise that he
      was evidently going to walk home with her. Perhaps, if she let him do all
      the talking, the companionship would help her to get over the ordeal of
      the return less miserably. But she could not, and she would not, talk.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I kind o&rsquo; thought mebbe you&rsquo;d shet up schewl fer a week &rsquo;r sao,&rdquo;
       he proceeded, ingratiatingly, &ldquo;but then agin I said to m&rsquo;self &lsquo;no siree,
      she ain&rsquo;t thet kine of a gal. Ef she&rsquo;s got any work to dew, she jes&rsquo; does
      it, rain &rsquo;r shine&rsquo;. Thet&rsquo;s what I said. Pooty bad business, wa&rsquo;n&rsquo;t
      it, this death of yer cousin?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dreadful!&rdquo; she murmured, wishing he would talk of something else.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sir, it&rsquo;s about&rsquo;s bad&rsquo;s they make &rsquo;em. Some queer things &rsquo;baout
      it tew. I s&rsquo;pose yeh ain&rsquo;t heerd no gossup &rsquo;baout it, hev yeh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; she whispered with a sinking heart; a real effort was needed to
      speak the other words: &ldquo;What gossip? Is there gossip?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dunnao&rsquo;s yeh kin call it real gossup. P&rsquo;raps nobuddy else won&rsquo;t &rsquo;spicion
      nothin&rsquo;. But to me they&rsquo;s some things &rsquo;baout it thet looks darned
      cur&rsquo;ous. Of caourse, it ain&rsquo;t none o&rsquo; my business to blab &rsquo;baout
      the thing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, of course.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      These little words, spoken falteringly, confirmed all that Milton had
      wished to learn the truth about. Over night a stupendous scheme had
      budded, unfolded, blossomed in his mind. Originally his primitive
      intellect had gone no further than the simple idea of committing homicide
      under circumstances which would inevitably point to an accident. The plan
      was clever in its very nakedness. But through some row among the women,
      probably out of jealousy, the hint of murder had been raised, and coupled
      with Seth&rsquo;s name. If this hint ripened into a suspicion and an inquiry, a
      new situation would be created, but Milton could not see any peril in it
      for him, for Seth would obviously be involved. But it would be better if
      no questions of murder were raised at all, and matters were allowed to
      stand. This would not only place Milton&rsquo;s security beyond peradventure,
      but it would give him a tremendous grip upon Annie. It was in this
      direction that his mind had been working steadily since he heard of
      Annie&rsquo;s suspicions. The opportunity seemed to have come for placing the
      cap-stone of acquisition upon the edifice of desire he had so long and
      patiently been rearing.
    </p>
    <p>
      As for the poor girl, she had reasoned herself out of the suspicion of
      Seth&rsquo;s guilt a thousand times, only to find herself hopelessly relapsing
      into the quagmire. Milton&rsquo;s hints came with cruel force to drag her back
      now, this time lower than ever. Even he seemed to know of it, but he
      proposed to maintain silence. Of course, he <i>must</i> be induced to keep
      silent. Oh! the agony of her thoughts!
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;n&rsquo; Seth was allus kine o&rsquo; frenly,&rdquo; he proceeded. &ldquo;Way back f&rsquo;m
      th&rsquo; time yeh was boys &rsquo;n&rsquo; gals.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, we always were.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; they used to say, daown to th&rsquo; corners, that yeou two was
      baoun&rsquo; to make a match of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There wasn&rsquo;t anything in that at all!&rdquo; She spoke decisively, almost
      peremptorily.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, they wa&rsquo;n&rsquo;t, ay?&rdquo; There was evident jubilation in his tone.
      &ldquo;Never was nothin&rsquo; in that talk, ay?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, nothing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The pair walked along on the side of the descending road silently for some
      moments. A farmer passed them, hauling a load of pumpkins up the hill, and
      exchanged a nod of salutation with Milton. This farmer remarked at his
      supper-table an hour later, to his wife: &ldquo;I&rsquo;d bet a yoke o&rsquo; oxen thet
      Milton Squires is a&rsquo;makin&rsquo; up to the schewl-teacher. I seed &rsquo;em
      walkin&rsquo; togither daown th&rsquo; hill to-night, &rsquo;n&rsquo; he was a lookin&rsquo; at
      her like a bear at a sap-trough. It fairly made me grit my teeth to see
      him, with his broadcloth cloze, &rsquo;n&rsquo; his watch-chain, &rsquo;n&rsquo; his
      on-gainly ways.&rdquo; To which his helpmeet acidulously responded: &ldquo;Well, I
      dunnao&rsquo;s she c&rsquo;d dew much better. She&rsquo;s gittin&rsquo; pooty well along, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      fer all his ongainly ways, I don&rsquo;t see but what he comes on, &lsquo;baout&rsquo;s
      well&rsquo;s some o&rsquo; them thet runs him daown. A gal can&rsquo;t jedge much by a man&rsquo;s
      ways haow he&rsquo;ll turn aout afterwards. <i>I</i> thought <i>I&rsquo;d</i> got a
      prize.&rdquo; Whereupon the honest yeoman chose silence as the better part.
    </p>
    <p>
      The red sun was hanging in a purplish haze over the edge of the hill as
      the two descended, and the leaves from Farmer Perkins&rsquo;s maples rustled
      softly under their feet. Milton drew near his subject:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve be&rsquo;n gittin&rsquo; on in th&rsquo; world sence yeou fust knew me, hain&rsquo;t I?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, everybody says so.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;&rsquo;N&rsquo; yit everybody don&rsquo;t knaow half of it. I ain&rsquo;t no han&rsquo; to tell
      all I knaow. Ef some folks c&rsquo;d guess th&rsquo; speckle-ations I be&rsquo;n in, &lsquo;n&rsquo; th&rsquo;
      cash I&rsquo;ve got aout in mor&rsquo;giges &rsquo;n&rsquo; sao on, it&rsquo;d make &rsquo;em
      open their eyes. It&rsquo;s th&rsquo; still saow thet gits th&rsquo; swill, as my mother
      use&rsquo; to say, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I&rsquo;ve be&rsquo;n still enough abaout it, I guess.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His coarse chuckle jarred on the girl&rsquo;s nerves, but the importance of
      placating him was uppermost in her mind, and she answered, as pleasantly
      as she could:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m sure I&rsquo;m glad, Milton. You have worked hard all your life, and you
      deserve it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yeh <i>air</i> glad, reely naow?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why yes! Why shouldn&rsquo;t I be? It always pleases me to hear of people&rsquo;s
      prosperity.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But me purtic&rsquo;ly?&rdquo; he persisted, earnestly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes,&rdquo; she replied, absent-mindedly. Then the odd nature of the
      question occurred to her, but she was too distrait to think consecutively,
      and she added no comment to her answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, it eases me to hear yeh say thet,&rdquo; he went on, with awkward
      deliberation, &ldquo;fer they&rsquo;s somethin&rsquo; I&rsquo;ve be&rsquo;n wantin&rsquo; to say to yeh fer a
      long time. I don&rsquo;t s&rsquo;paose you reelize haow well off I am?&rdquo; She did not
      answer. Her mind seemed to refuse to act, and she heard only the sound of
      his words. He took her reply for granted and continued:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I c&rsquo;d eena&rsquo;most buy up thet farm there&rdquo;&mdash;pointing over to the
      Fairchild acres on the slope, now within sight&mdash;&ldquo;&rsquo;n&rsquo; I ain&rsquo;t
      so all-fired sure yit thet I won&rsquo;t, nuther! But what&rsquo;s th&rsquo; good o&rsquo; money,
      on-less yeh kin git what yeh want with it, ay?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The impulse of her soul-weariness was to let this aimless question pass
      like the other, without reply. But she was reminded of the importance of
      being pleasant to this tedious man, and so answered, entirely at random:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What is it you want, Milton?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I dunnao&mdash;I&rsquo;m kind o&rsquo; feared o&rsquo; puttin&rsquo; my foot in it; yeh won&rsquo;t be
      mad ef I tell yeh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why no, of course not. What is it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, then,&rdquo; he blurted out, &ldquo;I want <i>yeou!</i>&rdquo; The girl looked dumbly
      at him, at first not realizing at all the meaning of his words, then held
      as in a vise between the disposition to reply to him as he deserved and
      the danger, the terrible danger, of angering him. There fluttered through
      her senses, too, a mad kind of yearning to shriek with laughter&mdash;born
      of the hysterical state of her long-oppressed nerves. She eventually
      neither rebuked nor laughed, but said vacuously:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Want <i>me?</i>&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ef yeou&rsquo;ll marry me, I&rsquo;ll make one o&rsquo; th&rsquo; fust ladies o&rsquo; Dearb&rsquo;rn Caounty
      aout o&rsquo; yeh. Yeh need never lay yer finger to a stitch o&rsquo; work agin, no
      more&rsquo;n Is&rsquo;bel did, daown yander.&rdquo; He spoke eagerly, with more emotion in
      his strident voice than she had ever heard there before.
    </p>
    <p>
      The difficulty of her position crushed her courage. Of course she must say
      no, but how do it without affronting him? The idea of reasoning him gently
      out of the preposterous wish came to her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;This is some flying notion in your head, Milton,&rdquo; she said, civilly. &ldquo;You
      will have forgotten it by next week.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Forgott&rsquo;n it, ay! Yeh think sao? What &rsquo;f I told yeh I hain&rsquo;t
      thought o&rsquo; nothin&rsquo; else fur nigh onto ten year?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His tone was too earnest and excited to render further trifling safe. He
      pulled out of an inner pocket and held up before her a little, irregularly
      squared tin-type&mdash;which she recognized as having been made in
      whimsical burlesque of her lineaments by an itinerant photographer years
      before.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How did you come by that?&rdquo; she asked, to gain time.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I got it fr&rsquo;m th&rsquo; man thet made it, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I paid a dollar bill fer
      it, tew,&rdquo; he answered triumphantly, &ldquo;&rsquo;n&rsquo; I&rsquo;ve kep it by me ever
      sence!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      After a pause she said, as calmly as she could: &ldquo;I never dreamed that such
      a thought had entered your head. Of course, it&mdash;it can&rsquo;t be.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why not, I&rsquo;d like to knaow?&rdquo; he demanded. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t yeh b&rsquo;lieve what I&rsquo;ve
      told yeh &rsquo;baout my bein&rsquo; well off?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That hasn&rsquo;t anything to do with it. There are other reasons&mdash;a good
      many other reasons.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What air they?&rdquo; His tone was peremptory.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know that I can explain them to you. But truly there are so many
      of them&mdash;and your words took me so wholly by surprise, that&mdash;that&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yeh needn&rsquo;t mince matters! I <i>knaow!</i> Yeh hev sot yer idees on Seth!
      Yeh needn&rsquo;t tell me yeh hain&rsquo;t!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I won&rsquo;t talk with you at all if you shout at me in that way, and
      contradict me flat when I assure you to the contrary.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Milton paused for a moment, to consider the situation. They were
      approaching the poplars now, along the lonely turnpike, and the
      conversation could not be much protracted. What he had to say must be said
      without delay. But what was it that he wished to say? A dozen inchoate
      plans rose amorphously to the surface of his mind&mdash;to cajole her, to
      strive further to impress her with his wealth, to entreat her, to attempt
      to bully her. This last resource ran best with his mood, but there were
      difficulties. Annie was the reverse of a cowardly girl; there was nothing
      timid or tremulous about her; if he attempted to intimidate her, the
      enterprise would most probably be a ridiculous failure, for he stood too
      much in awe of her self-reliance and intelligence to have confidence in
      his own mastery.
    </p>
    <p>
      But stay&mdash;she was fearful about Seth. Whether it was true or not that
      she had no idea of marrying her cousin, she was evidently solicitous for
      his safety. An idea born of this conclusion swiftly engrafted itself upon
      the hired man&rsquo;s general strategy. He lifted his light, shifty eyes from
      the grass of the roadside path to her face, once more, and said:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, ef you&rsquo;re a mine to be mean, I kin be mean tew&mdash;meaner &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      pussly. Ef yeh think I&rsquo;m goin&rsquo; to stan&rsquo; still, &rsquo;n&rsquo; let yeou &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      Seth hev it all yer aown way, yer mistaken. I&rsquo;ve only got to open my
      maouth to th&rsquo; Cor&rsquo;ner, &rsquo;n&rsquo; whair&rsquo;d <i>he</i> be, &rsquo;n&rsquo; yeou
      tew?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a certain indefinable suggestion of bravado in his tone which
      caught Annie&rsquo;s attention. It was the barest, most meagre of shadows, but
      she grasped at the chance of substance behind it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t believe you could say anything, or do anything, which would
      injure him,&rdquo; she said, with more confidence in her words than she felt in
      her heart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yeh daon&rsquo;t, ay!&rdquo; he growled. &ldquo;Ef yeh knaowed what I knaow, p&rsquo;raps
      yeh&rsquo;d change yer teune.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you know, then? Come now, let us hear it!&rdquo; She grew defiant, with
      an instinctive sense that the inferior being beside her was ready to
      retreat, if only she could keep up her boldness of front.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never yeou mind what I knaow!&rdquo; he answered, evasively. &ldquo;It&rsquo;ll be enough,
      I guess, to cook <i>his</i> geuse, when th&rsquo; time comes.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, I thought so!&rdquo; she exclaimed. &ldquo;You were simply talking to hear
      yourself talk&mdash;to scare me. Well, you see now that you wasted your
      breath.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, <i>did</i> I! Well, I won&rsquo;t waste any more of it, then, till I talk
      to th&rsquo; Cor&rsquo;ner. I kin tell him some things &rsquo;baout who rid th&rsquo; black
      mare aout thet night, after Albert&rsquo;d gone. Guess thet&rsquo;ll kind &rsquo;o&rsquo;
      fix things!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His slow imagination, working clumsily in the mazes of falsehood, had
      carried Milton a step too far; his simple plan of substituting Seth for
      himself in the events of the fatal night miscarried in a way he could not
      suspect.
    </p>
    <p>
      Annie did not answer. An exclamation had risen to her lips, but something
      akin to presence of mind checked it there. Her brain seemed to be working
      with lightning flashes. The black mare had played a part in the tragedy,
      then; Seth had certainly not had the animal out that evening; the rushing,
      almost noiseless apparition which had startled them in the moonlight must
      have been the mare; it was coming from the direction of Tallman&rsquo;s; it had
      a rider; who could that rider have been? and how did Milton know about it?&mdash;so
      the swift thoughts ran, in a chain which seemed luminous in the relief it
      brought to her. These two questions she could not answer&mdash;in her joy
      at the apparent exculpation of Seth it did not seem specially important
      that they should be answered&mdash;and she had self-possession enough to
      ask nothing about them.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was a nice question what she should say to her companion, who was now,
      without any distinct suspicions on her part, growing luridly loathsome and
      repugnant in her eyes. The fear of angering him had died away, but a vague
      sense that mischief might be done by arousing his curiosity or
      apprehensions had come to take its place. She spoke cautiously:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I hope you won&rsquo;t do anything rash, that you would regret afterwards.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They ain&rsquo;t nao need o&rsquo; my doin&rsquo; nothin&rsquo;, ef yeou&rsquo;d only hev some sense.
      But if yeou&rsquo;re goin&rsquo; to be agin me, ther&rsquo;s nao tellin&rsquo; what I won&rsquo;t dew,&rdquo;
       he answered with sullen terseness.
    </p>
    <p>
      They had come to the poplars, and Annie stopped at the stile under the
      thorns.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall have to leave you here,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then yeh won&rsquo;t hev me, ay? Yeh better think twice &rsquo;fore yeh say
      nao! Yeh won&rsquo;t git another sich a chance&mdash;to live like a lady, &rsquo;n&rsquo;
      hev ev&rsquo;rything yeh want. &rsquo;N&rsquo; ef yeh dew say nao, yeh kin rest &rsquo;sured
      yeh ain&rsquo;t heerd th&rsquo; last of it, ner him nuther.&rdquo; Milton&rsquo;s little
      green-gray eyes watched her face intently, and he fingered his flaring
      plated watch-chain with nervous preoccupation. &ldquo;What d&rsquo;yeh say, yes&rsquo; &rsquo;r
      nao?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t say anything more than I have said&mdash;<i>now</i>,&rdquo; she
      answered, and, stepping over the stile, left him.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a long time afterward Annie&rsquo;s conscience debated the justification of
      that final word, the last one she ever addressed to Milton, and which was
      obviously intended to keep alive a hope that she knew to be absurdly
      without ground or reason. Sometimes even now she has momentary doubts
      about it&mdash;but she silences cavil by whispering to herself in
      unanswerable defence: &ldquo;I thought then that possibly it might be needed to
      help Seth&mdash;perhaps even to save him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She had little leisure just then, however, to devote to moral
      introspection, for Samantha met her, half-way down the thorn-walk, to
      excitedly tell her that her grandmother, Mrs. Warren, was very much worse
      than usual.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
