    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXII.&mdash;&ldquo;A WICKED WOMAN!&rdquo;
     </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">W</span>hen Isabel looked
      into her mirror next morning, the image shown back fairly startled her.
      Day by day during this eventful week the glass had helped her to grow
      familiar with reddened eyes, with harsh, ageing lines, and with a pallor
      which no devices of the toilet could efface. It was not so much an added
      accentuation of these which riveted her gaze, now, upon the mirror, as the
      suggestion of a new face&mdash;of a stranger&rsquo;s countenance, reflecting
      meanings and thoughts of the uncommon kind.
    </p>
    <p>
      She studied the face at first with an almost impersonal interest; then as
      the brain associated these lineaments with her own, and made their
      expression a part of her own spiritual state, she said to this other self
      in the glass, audibly:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Another week of this will make you an old woman.&rdquo; She added, after a
      pause of fascinated yet critical scrutiny: &ldquo;Yes, and a wicked woman, too!&rdquo;
       There has been what one can only hope is an intelligible reluctance, from
      the beginning of this recital, to essay analysis or portrayal of Isabel&rsquo;s
      thoughts and motives. A complex, contradictory character like hers,
      striving now to assimilate, now to sway the simple, straightforward,
      one-stringed natures with which it is environed, may be illustrated; it is
      too great a task to dissect it. Yet for the once we may venture to look
      into this troubled mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      A wicked woman! The phrase which she had addressed aloud to the mocking
      image in the glass, in mingled doubt and irony, clung to her meditations.
      Had she ever meant to be wicked&mdash;ever deliberately, or even
      consciously, chosen evil instead of good? No! There was no dubious
      reservation in her answer. Yet within the week&mdash;oh, the horrible
      week!&mdash;she had come to occupy a moral position for which hell could
      not hold too relentless or fierce a punishment. She had hugged to her
      heart thoughts which, when they are linked with acts, go to expiation on
      the gallows. She shuddered now at the recollection of them; she could
      recall that she had shuddered then, too. Yet all the same these thoughts
      were a part of her&mdash;belonged to her. She had not repelled them as
      alien, or as unwelcome. Even while in terror at their mien, she had
      embraced them. Was this not all wickedness?
    </p>
    <p>
      The reply came, in sophistical self-defense, that no one act or emotion of
      a life could be judged by itself. The antecedent circumstances, leading up
      to it, must be taken into account. She had been borne along on the current
      of a career shaped for her by others. She was not responsible&mdash;she
      had never fought with her destiny&mdash;she had done nothing but seek to
      bring some flowers and light and color into the desolate voyage of life.
      Was it fair to say that these little innocent, womanish efforts to soften
      a sterile existence were the cause of the shipwreck&mdash;that it was
      these which had brought her so suddenly, dazed and terrified, into the
      very breakers on the sinister rocks of crime? No, the answer came again;
      surely it could not be fair.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yet she had hated her husband; she had been overjoyed, even while she was
      affrighted, by the news of his death&mdash;or at least there was a
      tremulous sensation very like joy; she had hailed as her deliverer the
      young man whom her wild fancy made responsible for that death&mdash;yes,
      had even in her frenzy kissed his hand, the hand which she then believed
      to have blood upon it, his brother&rsquo;s blood! her husband&rsquo;s blood! Were not
      these the thoughts and actions of a wicked woman? What difference was
      there between her and the vilest murderess confined for life in a
      penitentiary?
    </p>
    <p>
      Or no! What nonsense this was! What single thing had she said or done to
      bring on the catastrophe? It was an accident&mdash;everybody knew that
      now. But even if it had not been an accident, how would she have been to
      blame? Was it her fault that she was pleasing in men&rsquo;s eyes, or that Seth
      had been attracted by her, and had been sympathetic to her? How could she
      have helped it? Was there any reason why she should have tried to help it?
      Was it wrong for her, exiled as she was to this miserable farm life, to
      make a friend of her cousin&mdash;her husband&rsquo;s brother? And if they had
      grown to be attached to each other, could it be wondered at?
    </p>
    <p>
      And it had all been so innocent, too! What single compromising word, even,
      had ever been spoken! Might not the most blameless of women have had just
      such a pretty little romantic friendship, without dream of harm?
    </p>
    <p>
      As for the frantic things she had thought and said on that awful forenoon
      after the discovery, she strove to put them away from her memory, as born
      of a hysterical, wholly irresponsible state.
    </p>
    <p>
      But they would come back, no matter how often banished.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then, too&mdash;perhaps worst of all, for honest John seemed to lay
      particular stress upon it&mdash;was the terrible declaration she had made
      to Annie. About this there could be no self-deception. She would not
      pretend to herself that this had been done through any but revengeful?
      spiteful motives&mdash;pure cruelty, in fact. But was she to be thus
      coolly pushed aside, her romance shattered, her dear day-dream dissipated&mdash;and
      not to be justified in striking back?
    </p>
    <p>
      This conceited boy&mdash;she was able thus to think of Seth now, in his
      absence, and in the light of the affront she felt he had put upon her&mdash;and
      this country school-teacher, to come billing and cooing in the very hour
      of her supreme excitement&mdash;did they not deserve just what they had
      received? After all, her words had done no permanent harm.. Doubtless by
      this time they had all been cleared up. And if Miss Annie <i>did</i>
      suffer a little, what better was she than other people, to be free all her
      life from heartaches?
    </p>
    <p>
      But then came a mental picture of Annie&rsquo;s calm, sweet, lightful face
      transfixed with speechless horror at the brutal words&mdash;and after it,
      close and searching, the question: &ldquo;Why should I have stabbed Annie? She
      was always kindness itself to me. Was it not heartless to make that poor
      girl suffer?&rdquo; And there followed in her mind, as an echo of her first
      exclamation to the mirror&mdash;that had gathered reverberating force from
      all the thoughts we have striven to trace&mdash;the haunting cry: &ldquo;A
      wicked woman!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Afternoon came, and the battle still went on. Bitter condemnation of her
      own conduct struggled with angry pleas of grievance against others, and
      the conflict wearied her into what threatened to be a sick headache. The
      idea of getting out into the open air and seeking relief in a walk, which
      had been dormantly in her mind all day, finally took form, and led her
      outside the homestead for the first time since her husband&rsquo;s death.
    </p>
    <p>
      Once outside, she walked aimlessly through the orchard&mdash;in preference
      to the high road, where she might meet neighbors&mdash;toward the little
      family graveyard. It was not until she had nearly reached this spot that
      she recalled having heard that Seth, too, came here on that terrible
      night. The recollection brought an added sense of all the wrongs she held
      to have been done her. She stood for a long time by the old board fence,
      with its coating of dry, mildew-like moss on the weather-beaten surfaces
      turned to the north, and its inhospitable hedging of brown, half-bare
      briars, and looked in reverie upon the tombs within the enclosure.
    </p>
    <p>
      Three generations of the Fairchilds lay here under the straggling mat of
      withered strawberry vines. She saw the low blue-slate slabs, nearly
      covered now by aspiring weeds and brambles, which modestly pleaded in
      antique letters that the original shoemaker, Roger, and his lowly spouse
      might not be altogether forgotten. Rising ostentatiously above these
      timid, ancient memorials, as if with intent to divert attention from their
      humility, was the marble obelisk marking the resting-place of the family&rsquo;s
      greatest man, the Hon. Seth Fairchild. The monument was not so white or so
      imposing now as it once had been, and the proud inscription setting forth
      how its subject had been &ldquo;twice Senator of the State of New York,&rdquo; was
      almost illegible from the storm-stains and mould on its venerable front.
      There were some other stones, gray and small, tipping humbly toward the
      central monolith, as if mutely begging at least a little share of the
      Senator&rsquo;s greatness for his wife and sisters, and nearer were two plain
      modern slabs recounting the sole interesting facts of the colorless lives
      of Lemuel and Cicely Fair-child&mdash;that they had been alive, and now
      were dead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Here still nearer her, almost at her feet, the widow saw some pegs driven
      in the ground, with string stretched around them to form a long rectangle.
      The sight brought no thrill to her. She was conscious of all its meaning,
      but felt herself scarcely interested. In life she had owed nothing but
      dislike to the man whose last coming these signs of preparation betokened.
      His death had shocked her at first by its fearful suddenness; it did not
      especially disturb her now, save at times with a furtive elation at the
      accompanying thought that at last she was free. Her thoughts were with the
      living&mdash;and their relation to those long since dead.
    </p>
    <p>
      If these rambling thoughts could have been summarized in words they would
      have run in this fashion:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has all your family pride brought you, all your planning and
      manoeuvring, you dull countrymen? <i>I</i> wasn&rsquo;t good enough for you, eh?
      Your breed must conspire against me, eh? and treat me like an interloper,
      an outsider, eh? You thought I was to be brought here too, did you, when
      my time arrived, and be snubbed and bullied into some back corner like the
      rest of your wives, while my husband, &lsquo;the Congressman,&rsquo; had a big
      monument like this of your old humbug, the Senator? And you expected to
      patronize me, or cut me dead, as the living dolts here on the turnpike
      have done, did you? Well, you are fooled! I&rsquo;ve escaped you! I shall never
      come here but once again&mdash;to bring you your &lsquo;Congressman.&rsquo; You can
      have him and welcome. And that old cat of an aunt of his, she will come
      presently, too, and I wish you much joy of <i>her!</i> And perhaps you
      will give up your idea, then, that you amount to anything, or ever will
      amount to anything. The farm is going to a young man who will sell it, and
      who doesn&rsquo;t care a cent for the whole crowd of you, and who will live in a
      city, and eat with his fork, and forget that there ever were such people
      as you. And he will forget, too, that&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She came to a full stop in her meditations. Yes, Seth would forget her,
      too. She had no illusions on this point. Perhaps this was too kindly a
      view of it, even&mdash;he might be compelled to remember her by sheer
      force of his bitterness toward her. There could be no doubt, after his
      cruel words on the eventful forenoon&mdash;their last meeting&mdash;that
      he scorned and despised her. What an idiot she had been to disclose to him
      her thoughts&mdash;those mad fancies and beliefs of that frantic morning!
      She might have known that the idea of his fighting his brother, on <i>her</i>
      account, was preposterous. What did he care about her? He had been nice
      with her, had written her pretty, graceful letters when she asked him to
      do so, and had sent her books to read&mdash;that was all. There was
      nothing else. She had been a fool to dream that there was anything else.
      He would sell the farm, and go back to Tecumseh, and marry Annie&mdash;yes,
      marry Annie! And they, too, would refer to her now and then, and comment
      on her wickedness, and hope that they might never have a daughter like
      her. That would be all.
    </p>
    <p>
      She turned from the little enclosure of graves, without giving them
      another thought. The mental picture which she conjured up of the young
      couple, contented by a fireside of their own, perhaps with a child, tore
      at her heart-strings.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the farm-yard she was met by Mr. Ansdell, who was evidently watching
      for her, and who introduced himself courteously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The Coroner is here,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;with some medical gentlemen, and there
      are also your late husband&rsquo;s partner, Mr. Hubbard, who accompanied me from
      New York last night, and the District Attorney and some others. In a
      couple of hours or so we expect to be able to tell you what brought us.
      Meanwhile, we are anxious to spare you any possible intrusion&mdash;and
      also a possible scene. It is for this that I have waited outside for you.
      If you could prolong your walk for that length of time, going to some
      friend&rsquo;s house near by, for instance, without saying that anything unusual
      was transpiring here&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, I will go,&rdquo; she answered. &ldquo;Will two hours be long enough?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I hope so,&rdquo; he said, bowing his thanks.
    </p>
    <p>
      She walked out through the great swing-gate to the turnpike, and idly
      chose the westward turning, along under the poplars. The curious incident
      of all these visitors at the house did not excite her attention. Her mind
      was too busy torturing itself with that marriage which was already spoken
      of as assured.
    </p>
    <p>
      At the stile by the thorns, the idea of going to the Warren house suddenly
      occurred to her. It was a bold, purposeless, almost crazy thought; perhaps
      for those very reasons it commended itself to her mood. She felt herself
      impelled alike by good and malignant impulses to cross the stile; she
      walked down the thorn path, scarcely knowing whether her purpose was to
      bless or to curse.
    </p>
    <p>
      The door was opened by Samantha, whose scared face took on an added
      expression of anxiety on recognizing the visitor.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go into the parlor, &rsquo;n&rsquo; I&rsquo;ll light the stove fer yeh,&rdquo; she
      whispered. &ldquo;Th&rsquo; old lady&rsquo;s very laow. Soon&rsquo;s she comes hum from schewl
      I&rsquo;ll send Annie in to see yeh.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0033" id="link2HCH0033"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXIII.&mdash;THE SHERIFF ASSISTS.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">W</span>hile Isabel sat
      over the stove in the cold, austere parlor of the Warren house, with its
      ancient furniture, the never failing photograph album, and those huge pink
      shells on the mantle-shelf without which no rural home used to be complete&mdash;waiting
      for she scarcely knew what&mdash;strange things were going forward in the
      home of the Fairchilds.
    </p>
    <p>
      On the forenoon of this same day, Thursday, there had been a gathering in
      the office of the Thessaly <i>Banner of Liberty</i>. It was the
      publication day of the paper, but for once it went to press without
      enlisting even the most careless scrutiny, let alone the solicitude, of
      its editor-proprietor. He had more serious business on hand. Closeted with
      him in the little editorial room, whose limited space had rarely before
      been so taxed, were Beekman, Ansdell, the District Attorney, the Sheriff,
      and the younger of the dead man&rsquo;s two New York partners, a shrewd, silent,
      long-faced man. Seth had desired to be of the party but his brother had
      sent him off, to return after dinner.
    </p>
    <p>
      These men gravely discussed some subjects with which our readers are
      familiar, and some now first brought to light. John had a letter from
      Annie, sent by hand the previous evening, detailing the strange things
      Milton had said to her about the black mare. Ansdell and Mr. Hubbard, the
      partner, recited how they had discovered that Albert Fairchild, on the
      preceding Monday, sold $16,000 worth of government bonds, and the abortive
      effort he made to so arrange the transfer that it would not be traced.
      Beekman recalled how the black mare had balked on the edge of the gulf the
      day after the murder&mdash;for they all thus characterized it now. Later,
      the Coroner came in by appointment, and in the presence of the dreaded
      District Attorney was meekness itself. He even heard that two physicians
      were to go out with the party, and make an examination, without taking
      offence.
    </p>
    <p>
      After the noon-day dinner the gathering was reinforced by the two doctors
      and by Seth, the latter devoured by curiosity and vexed at being kept so
      long in the dark. Soon after, all of the party save the Sheriff made their
      way to the Fairchild house, driving by twos or threes, and at intervals,
      to avoid exciting suspicion. It was after the arrival of the last division
      that Ansdell met Isabel, and advised her to stay away from the house for a
      time.
    </p>
    <p>
      The two surgeons and the Coroner went silently into the parlor, and closed
      the door behind them. In the living-room Ansdell, Hubbard, John, and the
      District Attorney took chairs around the stove, having given word that
      Milton, who was off on the other side of the hill, arranging the sale of
      some apples, should be sent in to them when he arrived, which could not be
      very long now. In the kitchen, opening back from the living-room as this
      in turn did from the parlor, Seth and Beekman sat with the three women of
      the household.
    </p>
    <p>
      These latter had been told that something was going on, or rather had
      inferred it from being forbidden to leave the room, and were agog with
      puzzled excitement. They had no clue, save a vague understanding that
      important personages were in the front portions of the house, but Alvira
      and Melissa stole unhappy glances toward Seth, in uneasy fear that the
      worst suspicions born of Samantha&rsquo;s recital were to be realized in fact.
      Aunt Sabrina, sitting with her shawl wrapped about her gaunt shoulders,
      and with her feet on a piece of wood in the oven, did not know of this
      story which gave point to the other women&rsquo;s anxiety, but was in misery
      between a deep yearning to learn what had happened, and a pessimistic
      conviction that it must be another addition to the Fairchilds&rsquo; load of
      calamities.
    </p>
    <p>
      They heard Milton drive up presently, and hail Dana with instructions to
      put the horse out, and a query concerning the several strange vehicles
      under the shed. Then he came into the kitchen, stamping his feet with the
      cold, and walking straight to the stove to warm his hands. It was growing
      dark in the low room, and he did not recognize Beekman.
    </p>
    <p>
      Seth delivered his errand, saying that his brother John wished to see
      Milton, as soon as he returned, in the living-room. The hired man gave the
      speaker a curious glance, and, after a moment or two of hand warming, went
      in to learn what was wanted.
    </p>
    <p>
      Almost as he closed the door behind him, the Sheriff entered the kitchen
      from the outside, and after an interrogative glance toward Beekman, which
      the latter answered by a nod, drew up a chair leisurely by the stove.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who&rsquo;d a thought it &rsquo;d a turned out so cold, &lsquo;fore the moon
      changed?&rdquo; he asked of the company collectively. &ldquo;Hev yeh got any cider
      abaout handy? &rsquo;N&rsquo; a daoughnut, tew, ef yeh don&rsquo;t mine.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      While Melissa was in the cellar, the Sheriff, who was a Spartacus man and
      a stranger to both Seth and the females, asked of Beekman: &ldquo;What did yeh
      agree on fer a sign?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Th&rsquo; shakin&rsquo; of th&rsquo; stove.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Seth had been annoyed all day at the pains taken by John to keep the facts
      of the enterprise now in hand from him, and he displayed so much of this
      pique in the glance he now cast from the Sheriff to Beekman, that the
      latter felt impelled to speak:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;P&rsquo;raps you disremember my askin&rsquo; yeh &rsquo;t&rsquo; other day &rsquo;baout
      whether yer brother had much money on him that night. Well, we&rsquo;ve settled
      thet point. He did hev&rsquo;&mdash;&rsquo;n&rsquo; &rsquo;twas a considerable sum
      tew&mdash;&lsquo;baout sixteen thaousan&rsquo; dollars.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No!&rdquo; Seth&rsquo;s exclamation was of incredulous surprise.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, sixteen thaousan&rsquo;. We knaow it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! I remember now,&rdquo; said Seth, searching his impressions of the night.
      &ldquo;I remember that when I said he might fail to be nominated, he slapped his
      breast two or three times as if he had something in the pocket. By George!
      I wonder&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yeh needn&rsquo;t waste no more time wond&rsquo;rin&rsquo;. Thet was it! &rsquo;N&rsquo; d&rsquo;yeh
      knaow what he was goin&rsquo; to dew with thet money? No, yeh daon&rsquo;t! He was
      agoin&rsquo; to buy me! I wouldn&rsquo;t say this afore aoutsiders; I dunnao&rsquo;s I&rsquo;d say
      it to yeou ef your paper wa&rsquo;n&rsquo;t so dum fond o&rsquo; pitchin&rsquo; into me fer
      a boss, &rsquo;n&rsquo; a machine man ez yeh call it, &rsquo;n&rsquo; thet kine o&rsquo;
      thing. Yer brother hed th&rsquo; same idee o&rsquo; me thet your paper&rsquo;s got. He was
      wrong. They tell me ther air&rsquo; some country caounties in th&rsquo; State where
      money makes th&rsquo; mare gao. But Jay ain&rsquo;t one of &rsquo;em. Yer brother
      wanted to git into Congress. Ther was nao chance fer him in New York City.
      He come up here &rsquo;n&rsquo; he worked things pooty fine, I&rsquo;m baoun&rsquo; to say,
      but he slipped up on me. Bribes may dew in yer big cities, but they won&rsquo;t
      go daown in Jay. I don&rsquo;t b&rsquo;lieve they&rsquo;s ez much of it done anywhere ez
      folks think, nuther.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But this money, then, was&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Lemme go on! P&rsquo;raps this &rsquo;d never be&rsquo;n faound aout, ef yer brother
      hadn&rsquo;t made mistake number tew in pickin&rsquo; aout the wust &rsquo;n&rsquo; meanest
      cuss in th&rsquo; caounty to be his gao-between. I kin tell mean cusses when I
      see &rsquo;em, &rsquo;n&rsquo; this feller he had was jest <i>the</i> dirtiest
      scalawag I ever did see. I kin stan&rsquo; a scoundrel in a way ef he&rsquo;s bright
      abaout it, but this was a reg&rsquo;lar, natchul born fool. Somehaow in th&rsquo;
      kentry, these men don&rsquo;t seem to hev no sense. Ef they&rsquo;re goin&rsquo; to rob a
      man, or set his barns afire, or kill him, they dew it in the darnedest,
      clumsiest saort o&rsquo; way, so they&rsquo;re sure to git faound aout the minute
      anybody looks an inch beyond his nose into th&rsquo; thing. It makes a man
      ashamed to be a kentry-man to see th&rsquo; foolish way these here blockheads
      git caught, ev&rsquo;ry time.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The women had been listening intently to this monologue. They looked at
      one another now, with the light of a strange new suspicion in their eyes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who is this man? Who are you talking about?&rdquo; Seth asked eagerly.
    </p>
    <p>
      At that moment the sound of a stove being shaken vigorously came from the
      living-room. The Sheriff rose to his feet, and strode toward the door of
      this room.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll shaow him to yeh in th&rsquo; jerk of a lamb&rsquo;s tail,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      The conversation in the living-room, after Milton entered, had been
      trivial for a time, then all at once very interesting. He had been
      disagreeably surprised at finding three men with John, but had taken a
      seat, his big hands hanging awkwardly over his knees, and had been
      reassured somewhat by the explanation that Mr. Hubbard, the dead man&rsquo;s
      partner, was anxious to hear all he could about the sad occurrence. The
      District Attorney he did not know by sight, and he did not recognize
      Ansdell, who stood looking out of the window, softly drumming on the
      panes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Milton told a lot of details, about Albert&rsquo;s return, about hitching up the
      grays for him, about how the news was received at the Convention and the
      like, all recited with verbose indirectness, and at great length. Once he
      stopped, his attention being directed to a slight sound in the parlor, and
      looked inquiry. John promptly explained that it was the undertaker, and
      the hired man went on.
    </p>
    <p>
      At last the District Attorney, who had hitherto been silent, asked
      quietly:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You went back to the stable&mdash;to your own room&mdash;after Mr.
      Fairchild drove away?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, &rsquo;n&rsquo; went to bed.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Did you hear any one enter the stables afterward?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, nary a soul.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There is a black mare in the stables, used under the saddle. Was she
      taken out that night?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not thet I knaow of. Why?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, there seems to be a pretty positive story that she was. She was
      seen on the road, in fact, late that night, coming from the ravine. The
      rider was not recognized, but the mare was. How do you account for that?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tain&rsquo;t none o&rsquo; my business to &rsquo;caount for it.&rdquo; Milton did not like
      the tendency of the conversation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No, I know that, but we are interested in finding out. I don&rsquo;t think you
      know me&mdash;I am the District Attorney&mdash;and I shall take particular
      pains to find out.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A gulf suddenly yawned before Milton&rsquo;s feet, and he made a prompt, bold
      attempt to leap it. &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t like to say nothin&rsquo; &rsquo;baout it, bein&rsquo;
      as it&rsquo;s in th&rsquo; fam&rsquo;ly&rdquo;&mdash;he cast an uneasy glance at John here&mdash;&ldquo;but
      Seth Fairchild rides th&rsquo; mare a good deal. I did hear somebody saddlin&rsquo;
      th&rsquo; mare, but I took it fer granted it was him, &rsquo;n&rsquo; sao I didn&rsquo;t
      git up. It&rsquo;d be jes like him, I said to myself, to go ridin&rsquo; in th&rsquo;
      moonshine. He&rsquo;s thet sort of a feller, naow ain&rsquo;t he, John?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The sound of his own voice frightened Milton as he went on, and his
      closing appeal to the brother for corroboration carried the nervous accent
      of fear. John did not answer, but rose and walked over to join Ansdell at
      the window.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of caourse,&rdquo; Milton began, in a lower voice, to which he sought to give a
      confidential tone, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t wan&rsquo; to say nothin&rsquo; agin Seth. Of caourse,
      he&rsquo;s John&rsquo;s brother, &lsquo;n&rsquo;&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The words were cut short by the rolling back of one of the parlor doors,
      and the entrance of the three doctors. The Coroner, who came last, pulled
      the door shut again. The older of the other two came to the District
      Attorney and said, with deliberate distinctness:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We are both prepared to swear that Mr. Fairchild&rsquo;s death was caused by a
      gunshot wound in the head.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      It was then that John sprang to the stove, and shook its grate vehemently.
    </p>
    <p>
      At sight of the Sheriff, who advanced upon him with a directness which
      left no ambiguity as to his purpose, Milton rose excitedly from his chair,
      cast a swift scared glance around the company, and then, while the
      handcuffs were being snapped upon his wrists, began to whimper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t do it! It&rsquo;s a put-up job! It&rsquo;s them brothers o&rsquo; his thet allus
      hankered after his money, &rsquo;n&rsquo; naow they got it they&rsquo;re tryin&rsquo; to
      put the thing on me. &rsquo;N&rsquo; his wife, tew, thet stuck-up city gal, she&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Come naow, yeou better shut up,&rdquo; said the Sheriff sententiously. &ldquo;Th&rsquo;
      more yeh say th&rsquo; wuss it&rsquo;ll be fer yeh.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Most of the men present averted their gaze during the brief period of
      alternate threats and cringing, of rough curses and frenzied fawning on
      the Sheriff, the District Attorney, and even the Coroner, which ensued;
      but Mr. Hubbard watched it all carefully with evident interest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is a very curious type of criminal,&rdquo; he said, as the Sheriff and his
      prisoner left the room; &ldquo;very curious indeed! I never saw a murderer
      before who had so little nerve, and funked so absolutely when he was
      confronted with detection. Why, I&rsquo;ve seen men, guilty as guilty could be,
      who would deceive even their own lawyers. But such a simpleton as that&mdash;he&rsquo;s
      not worth his rope.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That is because you are a city man,&rdquo; explained the District Attorney.
      &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t know the kind of murderers we raise here in the country. The
      chances are that your city assassin would be tortured by remorse, if he
      escaped discovery, and that he committed the deed in a moment of passion.
      But the rural murderer (I am speaking of native Americans, now) plans the
      thing in cold blood, and goes at it systematically, with nerves like
      steel. He generally even mutilates the body, or does some other horrible
      thing, which it makes everybody&rsquo;s blood boil to think of. And so long as
      he isn&rsquo;t found out, he never dreams of remorse. He has no more moral
      perspective than a woodchuck. But when detection does come, it knocks him
      all in a heap. He blubbers, and tries to lay it on somebody else, and
      altogether acts like a cur&mdash;just as this fellow &rsquo;s doing now,
      for instance.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A hubbub of shrieks and sobs rose from the kitchen as he finished this
      sentence, and they with one accord moved toward the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Sheriff, with an eye to his promise to the two men in the kitchen, had
      led the livid and slinking wretch out to the centre of the room, where the
      dim candles had now been lighted, and, forcing him to hold up his hands so
      that the manacles might be fully visible, said to Seth:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Here yeh air! I said I&rsquo;d shaow him to yeh! Here is the whelp thet did th&rsquo;
      mischief. Look at him!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was a second of dead silence, as the several listeners took in the
      significance of his words, and of the spectacle.
    </p>
    <p>
      The silence was broken by an inarticulate, indescribable cry from Aunt
      Sabrina. Then came with startling swiftness a confusion of moving bodies,
      of screams, and the rattling of the handcuffs&rsquo; chain, which no one could
      follow. When the intervention of the Sheriff and Beekman had restored
      quiet, it was discovered that the old lady, with an agility of which none
      could have supposed her capable, had snatched a potato knife from the
      table, and made a savage attempt to wreak the family&rsquo;s vengeance upon
      Milton. She had not succeeded in inflicting any injury, save a slight cut
      on one of his pinioned hands, and Seth now with some difficulty persuaded
      her to leave the room.
    </p>
    <p>
      It fell to Alvira&rsquo;s lot to bind up the bleeding hand&mdash;for Melissa,
      undertaking the task, was too nervous and trembling to perform it.
    </p>
    <p>
      A little dialogue, in hushed whispers, which only imperfectly reached even
      the sentinel Sheriff, ensued:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Sao this is what yeh&rsquo;ve come tew!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s all a lie!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, don&rsquo;t tell <i>me!</i> Ef you&rsquo;d be&rsquo;n contented with yer lot in life,
      &rsquo;n&rsquo; hadn&rsquo;t tried to swell yerself up like a toad in a puddle, this
      wouldn&rsquo;t a happen&rsquo;d. But nao, yeh poor fewl, yeh must set yerself up to <i>be</i>
      somebody! &rsquo;N&rsquo; naow where air yeh?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Words with which to answer rose to Milton&rsquo;s bloodless lips, but he could
      not give them utterance. He could not even look at her, but in a dazed way
      stared at the hand, which he held so that she could wind the bandage in
      spite of the gyves.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t use to think yeh was aout-&rsquo;n-aout bad,&rdquo; she continued, more
      slowly; &ldquo;they was a time when yeh might a made a decent man o&rsquo; yerself&mdash;ef
      yeh&rsquo;d kep&rsquo; yer word to me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      This time he did not make an effort to answer.
    </p>
    <p>
      The task of sustaining the talk alone was too great for her. The tears
      came into her eyes, and blinded the last touches to the bandage. As it was
      completed, the Sheriff put his hand roughly on the prisoner&rsquo;s shoulder.
      The meaning of this movement spread over her mind, and appalled her. With
      a gesture of decision she stood on tiptoe, lifted her face up to Milton&rsquo;s,
      and kissed him. Then, as he was led away, she turned to the onlookers, and
      said defiantly, between incipient sobs:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I daon&rsquo;t keer! Ef t&rsquo; was th&rsquo; last thing I ever done in my life, I&rsquo;d dew
      it. We was&mdash;engaged&mdash;once&rsquo;t on a time!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0034" id="link2HCH0034"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXIV.&mdash;AT &ldquo;M&rsquo;TILDY&rsquo;S&rdquo; BEDSIDE AGAIN.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">D</span>o you clip over
      and tell Annie,&rdquo; John had said to Seth, when the first excitement of the
      scene had passed off, and they stood at the kitchen window, watching the
      Sheriff&rsquo;s buggy fade off in the dusk down the hill toward Thessaly jail.
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the thing for you to do&mdash;the quicker the better!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Annie had been home from her day&rsquo;s task some minutes, and sat by her
      grandmother&rsquo;s bedside. The patient was in a semi-comatose state, breathing
      with unnatural heaviness, and Samantha had been dispatched with all haste
      to bring a doctor from Thessaly. It seemed terribly probable that Mrs.
      Warren&rsquo;s last day had come.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yet as she sat by the curtained recess, holding in her&rsquo;s the withered hand
      which lay inanimate on the high edge of the bed, Annie still thought very
      little of the great change impending over her home; she had faced this
      death in life so long that its climax did not startle her, or wear the
      garb of strangeness. Instead, she was pondering the unaccountable,
      unwelcome fact with which Samantha had greeted her on her return&mdash;that
      Isabel was in the adjoining room, and had asked to see her.
    </p>
    <p>
      What could it mean? What could Isabel&rsquo;s purpose be in coming? And ought
      she to sacrifice her own feelings to the dictates of politeness, and go in
      to see this wicked, cruel woman? Perhaps she had come to retract and
      apologize for the fearful words of Tuesday. Perhaps her intention was to
      reiterate them, or worse, to recount that now the whole world would know
      of them&mdash;and gloat over her pain. No, that could scarcely be, for
      since her interview with Milton Annie felt satisfied at least of Seth&rsquo;s
      innocence. But still something new might have been disclosed&mdash;Isabel
      might have evil tidings of some sort with which to overwhelm her afresh.
      What should she do?
    </p>
    <p>
      The parlor door was ajar, and though she could not see her visitor, she
      could plainly hear the snapping of the wood fire within, which Samantha
      had kindled. Isabel must be perfectly aware of her return, and of her
      presence in this sick chamber. Every minute that she hesitated would only
      augment the widow&rsquo;s anger at being thus inhospitably neglected. Even if
      she had relented, and had come with kindly intent, this reception might
      alter her impulses.
    </p>
    <p>
      She rose to enter the parlor, but still stood irresolute, holding her
      grandmother&rsquo;s hand, when there came the sound of footsteps in the front
      hall&mdash;then of a hasty knock on the door opening from the hall into
      this room in which she was. She opened the door, and before her, excited
      and jubilant, stood her cousin Seth.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve come to tell you!&rdquo; he burst out, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s all cleared up. There <i>was</i>
      a murder. Milton did it! He&rsquo;s just been arrested! I tried to ring your
      bell, but it didn&rsquo;t seem to work. So I <i>had</i> to come in! And now&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He opened his arms with an unmistakable gesture, and they closed fondly
      upon an overjoyed maiden, who sobbed upon his breast for very relief.
    </p>
    <p>
      When she found breath and words, it was to say:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, you can&rsquo;t guess what I have suffered these last two days; I thought I
      should never live through them! And now it seems as if I should go wild
      with joy&mdash;as if I couldn&rsquo;t keep my feet down on the floor!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, yes, I know, my darling. But we shall be all the happier for this
      spell of wretchedness. Dry your eyes, pet. There shall be no more thought
      or talk of tears&mdash;much less of dying.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;O Seth!&mdash;I forgot!&mdash;my grandmother!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She lowered her voice, and told him her fears.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hand in hand, and with his arm about her shoulder, they moved softly to
      the bedside of the dying woman. The noise of the talking, or some less
      apparent influence, had aroused her from her lethargy. Her pale eyes were
      brilliant still, with an unearthly light, it seemed to the awed young man,
      and she rested their gaze fixedly upon the couple.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who is that?&rdquo; she asked in a querulous whisper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is Seth, Granny,&rdquo; the girl answered, relapsing unconsciously into the
      familiar form she had not used since childhood.
    </p>
    <p>
      The aged woman restlessly moved her head, and her eyes snapped with
      impatience at her inability to raise herself from the pillow.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I won&rsquo;t have him here! Tell him to take his arm away. What&rsquo;s he doin&rsquo;
      here, anyway? He desarted yeh! His own father told me so! Tell him to go
      away! I hate the sight of the hull breed!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But he&rsquo;s come back to me, Granny,&rdquo; the girl pleaded, while Seth shrank
      backward in the shadow of the curtain. &ldquo;Truly he has, and he&rsquo;s not to
      blame. And I love him very dearly&rdquo;&mdash;a pressure from the young man&rsquo;s
      hand answered the sweetness of this avowal&mdash;&ldquo;and he will be all I
      shall have left when&mdash;when&mdash;&rdquo; she stopped, unwilling to conclude
      her thought in words.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;An&rsquo; will he take yeh away, an&rsquo; do by yeh ez a husban&rsquo; ought to do, or
      will he take yeh onto that Fairchild farm, an&rsquo; break yer heart out ez his
      father did his mother&rsquo;s, an&rsquo; ez his uncle did yer mother&rsquo;s, an&rsquo; ez his
      brother, so they tell me, is doin&rsquo; with his wife?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, mercy!&rdquo; the girl exclaimed, involuntarily; then she whispered to
      Seth, back of the curtains: &ldquo;What shall I do! I forgot all about it&mdash;Isabel
      is there in the parlor and she has heard every word we&rsquo;ve said.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The quick ears of the invalid caught the whispered explanation. .
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Isabel!&rdquo; she said, sharply. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s Albert Fairchild&rsquo;s wife ain&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes!&rdquo; the girl answered. She tried in dumb show to convey to Seth that
      her grandmother was ignorant of his brother&rsquo;s death.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go an&rsquo; fetch her in here,&rdquo; said Mrs. Warren, with more animation in her
      voice than it had shown before. &ldquo;I want to see her&mdash;to talk with
      her.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But, Granny, you ought&rsquo;nt to see strangers; you know, the doctor&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I guess she ain&rsquo;t much more of a stranger than this young man you&rsquo;ve got
      here. Go an&rsquo; fetch her, I say! I won&rsquo;t hurt her, an&rsquo; she won&rsquo;t hurt me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was nothing for Annie to do, but go into the parlor, and bow
      shamefacedly to Isabel, and say, with embarrassment in every syllable:
      &ldquo;Excuse me for not coming before, but I think my grandmother is dying. She
      wants very much to see you. Won&rsquo;t you come, please?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel had risen to her feet upon Annie&rsquo;s entrance. To the latter&rsquo;s
      surprise and increased confusion she held forth her hand with a friendly
      gesture. &ldquo;Yes, I will come with you,&rdquo; she said, as Annie doubtingly took
      the proffered hand, and the two women entered the sick-room.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel did not seem to see Seth, who stood at the head of the bed, among
      the drawn curtains, but walked to the bedside and said softly: &ldquo;I am
      Isabel, Mrs. Warren; I am sorry that our first meeting should find you so
      low.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you&rsquo;re Albert&rsquo;s wife, eh?&rdquo; The old woman eyed her keenly, for what
      seemed a long time. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve heered tell o&rsquo; you. Would you mind gettin&rsquo; that
      candle there, on the mantle-piece, an&rsquo; holdin&rsquo; it, so&rsquo;t I kin see yer
      face?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel gravely complied with the request, and stood before the invalid
      again, with the yellow light glowing upon her throat and lower chin and
      nostrils and full, Madonna-like brows. Her face was at its best with this
      illumination from below. She would have been a rare beauty close before
      the footlights.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well,&rdquo; said Mrs. Warren, after a long inspection, &ldquo;P&rsquo;raps it&rsquo;ll sound
      ridiculous to yeh, but yeh don&rsquo;t look unlike what I did when I was your
      age. The farm ain&rsquo;t had time to tell on yeh yit. But it will! It made me
      the skeercrow that you see; it&rsquo;ll do the same for you. When I was a girl,
      I was a Thayer, the best fam&rsquo;ly in Norton, Massachusetts. We held our
      heads high, I kin tell yeh. Why, when I brought my side-saddle here,
      stitched with silk, &rsquo;twas the fust one they&rsquo;d ever seen in these
      parts. But I married beneath me, an&rsquo; I come up here into York State to
      live, on this very farm. With us, farmin&rsquo; don&rsquo;t mean a livin&rsquo; death.
      P&rsquo;raps we don&rsquo;t hev sech fine big barns ez yeh build here, but our houses
      are better. We don&rsquo;t git such good crops, but we pay more heed to
      education and godly livin&rsquo;. It&rsquo;s th&rsquo; diff&rsquo;rence &rsquo;twixt folks who
      b&rsquo;lieve there&rsquo;s somethin&rsquo; else in life b&rsquo;sides eatin&rsquo; an&rsquo; drinkin&rsquo; an&rsquo;
      makin&rsquo; money, an&rsquo; folks that don&rsquo;t. Well, I left a good home, an&rsquo; I come
      here, an&rsquo; here I am. Look at me! Look at Lemuel Fairchild&rsquo;s wife, Cicely&mdash;she
      was a relation of yours, wasn&rsquo;t she?&mdash;see how the farm made an ole
      woman o&rsquo; her, an&rsquo; broke her down, an&rsquo; killed her! You&rsquo;re young, an&rsquo; you&rsquo;re
      good lookin&rsquo; yit, but it&rsquo;ll break yeh, sure&rsquo;s yer born. Husban&rsquo;s on these
      farms ain&rsquo;t what they air in the cities, nor even in the country in New
      England. I&rsquo;m told your husban&rsquo; don&rsquo;t treat you right.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t let us talk about that&mdash;please!&rdquo; said Isabel: she stole a
      swift, momentary glance toward Seth as she spoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      The keen eyes in the recess followed this look. &ldquo;Well, no,&rdquo; the husky,
      whispering voice went on, &ldquo;p&rsquo;raps it ain&rsquo;t none o&rsquo; my business. But tell
      me about this young man here&mdash;yer husband&rsquo;s brother. I want to know
      about him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What about him?&rdquo; asked Isabel slowly, after a pause.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why, is he a likely man? Air his habits good? Could he take this girl o&rsquo;
      mine&mdash;an&rsquo; she&rsquo;s a good girl, Annie is&mdash;could he take her to
      Tecumsy, an&rsquo; make a fit home fer her? An&rsquo; <i>would</i> he do it? Would he
      make her a good husban&rsquo;&mdash;ez good ez she desarves? I ask you, &rsquo;cause
      you know him. I leave it to you&mdash;would you yerself marry him ef yeh
      was free, an&rsquo; feel safe about him? Come, now, tell me that!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Isabel hesitated so long that the old woman, seemingly wandering a little
      after her long, laborious concentration of thought, broke in again:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I know &rsquo;em! I know &rsquo;em! Of all the Fair-childses, there
      never was one decent one. They stole my daughter, an&rsquo; let her die &rsquo;mongst
      strangers, an&rsquo; they made a broken ole woman o&rsquo; me, an&rsquo; they slaved
      Cicely&rsquo;s life out o&rsquo; her, an&rsquo; now they want my Annie&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No,&rdquo; said Isabel here, speaking softly, and putting her hand on the
      wasted arm which lay above the coverlet. &ldquo;I think you wrong Seth. Whatever
      the rest may have done, I think he will be a good husband to Annie. I am
      <i>sure</i> he will.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      No answer, save a low, incoherent murmuring, came from the recess. The
      invalid had lapsed into the lethargy of exhausted nature. As the trio
      stood by the bedside even this sound ceased. Nothing was to be heard but
      the labored, unnatural breathing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Isabel placed the candle again upon the shelf. She had not removed her
      bonnet and wrap, and she turned now irresolutely toward the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      Annie went to her, and silently took her hand. &ldquo;I forgive you,&rdquo; she
      whispered. &ldquo;Was there anything else? Did you want to speak to me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know what I wanted when I came. Let me go now. Perhaps if I said
      any more, I should hate myself afterward.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And thus, without a glance at Seth, she went.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0035" id="link2HCH0035"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXXV.&mdash;&ldquo;SUCH WOMEN ARE!&rdquo;
     </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>HE story, such as
      it is, is told.
    </p>
    <p>
      Before the daily press of the State, which had given great attention to
      the tragedy in Dearborn County, became fairly aware that a mystery
      attached to it, the wretched Milton had confessed his crime. He had
      followed and come up with his employer, who stopped at his call. There was
      a conversation&mdash;then the killing. The prisoner made a weak effort to
      pretend that there was a quarrel first, and that his deed was in
      self-defence, but he deceived no one. He had with much difficulty led the
      grays off the side of the ravine, the murdered man being first thrown
      over, and the horses and buggy purposely hurled down upon him. There was
      some angry criticism when it became known that the District Attorney had
      agreed to accept a plea of murder in the second degree, and the popular
      explanation&mdash;that it was done from motives of consideration for the
      family&mdash;provoked not a few jibes from people who wanted to know why
      the Fairchilds were any better than other folk. But the course of the law
      was not affected by this comment, nor did the District Attorney suffer
      appreciably from it when he came up the succeeding autumn for re-election.
      The money was all recovered&mdash;and, if you have the influence requisite
      to obtain a visiting pass to New York&rsquo;s forest-girt prison on the Eastern
      watershed of the Adirondacks&mdash;that terrible subterranean place of woe
      from which even Siberian gaolers might get some hints of new things in
      anguish&mdash;you may still see a thin, bent, evil-faced wretch dragging
      out existence in the mines, who once was reckoned a likely man in Dearborn
      County, and who cast its united vote at the most famous of all Tyre&rsquo;s
      Conventions.
    </p>
    <p>
      The funeral of Albert Fairchild will long be remembered in all the section
      round. More than one State official attended, and there was a vast
      concourse of lesser political lights, who kept a shrewd eye upon
      opportunities for profitable discourse with each other, before and after
      the services, while they put themselves dignifiedly in evidence before the
      public by getting their names in the local papers.
    </p>
    <p>
      There were no surprises to the inner circle of the family when the will
      came to be read. Subject to the widow&rsquo;s third, the farm was devised in
      equal parts to the two brothers, but the major share of the other property
      went to Seth. The partner from New York remained at the homestead long
      enough to arrange the details by which the widow&rsquo;s portion was bought by
      the brothers, and her leave-taking accomplished.
    </p>
    <p>
      John Fairchild lives in high contentment on the ancestral farm. He grows
      stout now, in the accustomed Fairchild fashion, and though his light ruddy
      face and brown beard are hostile to the suggestion, people profess to see
      the family likeness in him as he grows older. Aunt Sabrina especially
      cherishes this fancy with fondness. She has come to regard this nephew,
      whom once she so deeply disliked, with some affection and vast esteem, and
      she devotes her hours to dreaming of the great things he may accomplish as
      the Fairchild of Dearborn&mdash;what time she is not joining Alvira in
      prayer that he may not be moved to marry a city woman. Thus far there are
      no indications that he thinks of marrying any one, and his ambitions seem
      to take no higher form than the re-invigoration of the <i>Banner of
      Liberty</i>, which he drives over to Thessaly three times a week to
      superintend, and which, they say, promises soon to blossom into a daily.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <p>
      One closing scene we may glance at&mdash;a pretty room, with modern
      furniture, and wide, flower-clad windows looking upon one of the best of
      Tecum-seh&rsquo;s residential streets. Annie, grown brighter-faced and yet no
      older in looks, despite the nearly four years of married life which have
      gone by, stands at the window with a baby in her arms, and laughs as she
      tosses the infant forward toward the panes, in greeting to the paternal
      parent, who is coming up the front steps. The wife is in gay spirits, not
      only because the head of the house has come home to dinner instead of
      stopping at the Club, but for another reason, compared with which all
      dinners were trivial.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;O Seth, her first tooth has come through!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That so? It&rsquo;s about time, I should-think.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      His reception of the great tidings is so calm, not to say indifferent,
      that the beaming wife looks at him in mock surprise. Seth has not aged
      specially either, but he wears this evening an unwontedly serious
      expression of face, and gets into his dressing-gown and slippers with an
      almost moody air.
    </p>
    <p>
      Baby is brought up in frowning, blinking proximity to her sire and made by
      proxy to demand an explanation of this untoward gloom, on an occasion
      which ought to be given over to rejoicing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, I&rsquo;m tired,&rdquo; Seth answers; &ldquo;and then&mdash;then I have a letter which
      puzzles and annoys me a little.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Is it anything that I know about?&rdquo; Annie has seated herself beside him
      now, and looks sweet inquiry.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, yes. It is a letter from Dent&mdash;you know I&rsquo;ve let him go down
      to Washington to get an idea of the place and the men while the session is
      on&mdash;and along with a letter to the paper, pretty good stuff, too, he
      sends me this personal note. Read it for yourself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Annie took the letter, and reads steadily along through its neat
      chirography:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Washington, March 7th.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Dear Fairchild:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I send a letter going into the Silver question from the standpoint of
      some of the Western men I have talked with. They impress me as being more
      sincere than sensible on the subject. I think the trip will be of vast
      service to me&mdash;and also, I trust, to the paper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Last evening, I met for the second time since I have been here, an
      elderly gentleman from your part of the State, named Beekman. Like myself,
      he is down here to look around, and get an idea of things. It is the first
      time, I should judge, that he has been so far away from home, and his
      comments are extremely droll&mdash;often very clever, too. He seems to
      know you very well, and asked me to remember him kindly to you, and
      express his congratulations upon your purchase of a controlling interest
      in the paper. He wanted me to be sure and say to you that while the
      experiment of electing Ansdell had worked very well&mdash;he seems to
      admire Ansdell greatly&mdash;you mustn&rsquo;t allow that to lead you into the
      habit of thinking that all bolters are saints and all straight-party men
      devils. It seems that since he has been here he has encountered some
      foolish and exceptional Southern Congressman who provoked him by saying &lsquo;<i>Your</i>
      Government&rsquo; and <i>your</i> laws&rsquo; instead of using the pronoun and that
      has made him a great Stalwart again&mdash;for the time-being.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Annie looked up from the sheet. &ldquo;I must say I don&rsquo;t see anything in all
      this to particularly disturb anybody. This seems just the harmless sort of
      letter I should expect your innocuous Mr. Dent to write.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Read the rest of it,&rdquo; was Seth&rsquo;s reply.
    </p>
    <p>
      She went on:&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By the way, I met your sister-in-law among the guests at a reception the
      other evening, to which Mr. Ansdell kindly secured me an invitation. Her
      residence on K street&mdash;she gave me the number, which I have somewhere&mdash;is
      said to be one of the most charming homes in Washington. She is
      very-popular in society here, and I am told that you meet her at every
      fashionable gathering. She was certainly very pleasant with me, when Mr.
      Ansdell presented me and explained who I was. She especially asked me if I
      knew what you had named your baby-girl, but I could not tell her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>I</i> could tell her if she asked <i>me!</i>&rdquo; remarked the young wife,
      grimly. &ldquo;The very idea!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go on,&rdquo; said Seth&mdash;&ldquo;or I shall feel that we ought to have named her
      Proscrastinatia instead of Annie; get to the end of the thing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Annie got to the end with a single sentence:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;By the way, it may interest you&mdash;and I hope you won&rsquo;t be annoyed at
      my mentioning it, and indeed you may very possibly have heard it already&mdash;to
      learn that everybody here seems to understand that Mr. Ansdell is shortly
      to marry your sister-inlaw, and he himself, speaking to me, referred to
      her in a way which amounted to a declaration of the fact.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, there you have it!&rdquo; said Seth slowly, after a long pause in which
      husband and wife looked at each other. &ldquo;That <i>is</i> news, isn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should think so!&rdquo; Annie spoke deliberately, too, turning the letter
      over with a meditative air. &ldquo;I should think so!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The gravity of his wife&rsquo;s tone seemed to Seth to be more profound than the
      circumstances altogether demanded.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know after all,&rdquo; he said, in half-apology for his own earlier
      confession of gloom, &ldquo;but that it would be a tolerable match. I don&rsquo;t say
      that they would be happy in the sense that we are happy, my girl; but she
      has a great many qualities which would make her a helpful wife to an
      ambitious, successful, masterful sort of public man like Ansdell. Come,
      now, let&rsquo;s be fair to her. Dent says that she is very popular in
      Washington.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes,&rdquo; replied Annie thoughtfully, drawing her daughter closer to her
      breast, &ldquo;she always will be popular with people who are not married to
      her. Such women are!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <h3>
      THE END.
    </h3>
